WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:34.630 align:middle line:90%


00:00:34.630 --> 00:00:36.130 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA MEREDITH:
If you're female,

00:00:36.130 --> 00:00:40.030 align:middle line:84%
over 40, married with kids, or
making waves in your career,

00:00:40.030 --> 00:00:42.660 align:middle line:84%
you've probably noticed some
irregularities in your body

00:00:42.660 --> 00:00:45.320 align:middle line:84%
shape or size, in
your sleep or mood.

00:00:45.320 --> 00:00:47.260 align:middle line:84%
According to Doctor
Sara Gottfried,

00:00:47.260 --> 00:00:50.290 align:middle line:84%
author of "The Hormone
Cure," hormonal imbalances

00:00:50.290 --> 00:00:53.480 align:middle line:84%
account for most of our weight,
sleep, and mood disorders.

00:00:53.480 --> 00:00:55.490 align:middle line:84%
The good news is
that these imbalances

00:00:55.490 --> 00:00:58.870 align:middle line:84%
can be corrected naturally,
without pharmaceuticals.

00:00:58.870 --> 00:01:01.740 align:middle line:84%
This means that we can feel
juicy and alive again--

00:01:01.740 --> 00:01:05.500 align:middle line:84%
if quality of life is a priority
worth putting some education

00:01:05.500 --> 00:01:07.770 align:middle line:90%
and effort into.

00:01:07.770 --> 00:01:09.270 align:middle line:84%
It's so nice to be
sitting with you.

00:01:09.270 --> 00:01:12.160 align:middle line:10%
I think I have
about 100 dog-ears

00:01:12.160 --> 00:01:14.270 align:middle line:10%
on the pages of your book
because this is actually

00:01:14.270 --> 00:01:15.600 align:middle line:10%
very useful information.

00:01:15.600 --> 00:01:18.070 align:middle line:10%
And you're getting
a lot of publicity

00:01:18.070 --> 00:01:19.580 align:middle line:10%
as a result of what you've done.

00:01:19.580 --> 00:01:21.121 align:middle line:10%
You're trying to
help women take back

00:01:21.121 --> 00:01:24.620 align:middle line:10%
their own hormonal health,
which feeds into stress,

00:01:24.620 --> 00:01:27.150 align:middle line:10%
and a lot of things that--
to the point where virtually

00:01:27.150 --> 00:01:29.280 align:middle line:10%
everybody needs to
understand these things.

00:01:29.280 --> 00:01:30.804 align:middle line:84%
So let's start
with your own story

00:01:30.804 --> 00:01:32.970 align:middle line:84%
because you've been through
your own load of stress.

00:01:32.970 --> 00:01:34.370 align:middle line:90%
You're a braniac.

00:01:34.370 --> 00:01:38.800 align:middle line:84%
Harvard, Harvard-trained,
MIT, engineer, doctor.

00:01:38.800 --> 00:01:40.850 align:middle line:84%
You've gone over
into this field now.

00:01:40.850 --> 00:01:42.530 align:middle line:84%
Give us your own
background and how

00:01:42.530 --> 00:01:44.382 align:middle line:90%
you ended up in this position.

00:01:44.382 --> 00:01:45.340 align:middle line:90%
>>SARA GOTTFRIED: Sure.

00:01:45.340 --> 00:01:46.930 align:middle line:10%
Well, I would
definitely say, Regina,

00:01:46.930 --> 00:01:49.620 align:middle line:10%
that it started with
my great-grandmother.

00:01:49.620 --> 00:01:52.350 align:middle line:10%
I want to honor her
first because she was not

00:01:52.350 --> 00:01:53.850 align:middle line:10%
the typical grandmother
who shows up

00:01:53.850 --> 00:01:57.870 align:middle line:10%
at your house with Barbies
and gum, See's candy.

00:01:57.870 --> 00:02:00.530 align:middle line:10%
She showed up with
kale, carob cookies.

00:02:00.530 --> 00:02:03.720 align:middle line:10%
And she was a serious
yogini way before there

00:02:03.720 --> 00:02:06.490 align:middle line:10%
was a yoga studio on
every street corner.

00:02:06.490 --> 00:02:08.639 align:middle line:84%
And she taught me a
really important lesson,

00:02:08.639 --> 00:02:12.200 align:middle line:84%
which is that you don't
find the answer to health

00:02:12.200 --> 00:02:13.960 align:middle line:90%
in a prescription pill bottle.

00:02:13.960 --> 00:02:16.570 align:middle line:84%
You find it in how you
craft your lifestyle.

00:02:16.570 --> 00:02:19.347 align:middle line:84%
You find it in the way
that you use your fork,

00:02:19.347 --> 00:02:21.430 align:middle line:84%
the way that you eat, move,
think, and supplement.

00:02:21.430 --> 00:02:22.470 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Wise woman.

00:02:22.470 --> 00:02:23.678 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: Very wise woman.

00:02:23.678 --> 00:02:26.660 align:middle line:84%
Slept on a board,
outlived four husbands.

00:02:26.660 --> 00:02:29.920 align:middle line:84%
But really, it wasn't
until I was in my 30s

00:02:29.920 --> 00:02:31.657 align:middle line:84%
that this really
made sense to me.

00:02:31.657 --> 00:02:34.240 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And by then, you had
already gone to medical school.

00:02:34.240 --> 00:02:36.580 align:middle line:84%
She said you're not going to
find your answers in a pill,

00:02:36.580 --> 00:02:37.440 align:middle line:90%
yet you went for the pill.

00:02:37.440 --> 00:02:38.710 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: And then I
went to medical school.

00:02:38.710 --> 00:02:40.710 align:middle line:84%
So I went to learn all
about the pills, right?

00:02:40.710 --> 00:02:41.200 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:02:41.200 --> 00:02:42.500 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: And
that is the nature

00:02:42.500 --> 00:02:43.700 align:middle line:90%
of conventional medicine.

00:02:43.700 --> 00:02:46.190 align:middle line:84%
We live in a culture--
and the medical industry

00:02:46.190 --> 00:02:48.100 align:middle line:84%
is part of this--
that believes that you

00:02:48.100 --> 00:02:50.190 align:middle line:84%
do find the answer
in a pill bottle.

00:02:50.190 --> 00:02:51.550 align:middle line:90%
And I disagree with that.

00:02:51.550 --> 00:02:54.810 align:middle line:84%
So I had a defining
moment when I was my 30s.

00:02:54.810 --> 00:02:58.790 align:middle line:90%
I was practicing McMedicine.

00:02:58.790 --> 00:03:01.910 align:middle line:84%
I was working at a health
maintenance organization.

00:03:01.910 --> 00:03:05.280 align:middle line:84%
I was seeing somewhere
around 30 patients a day.

00:03:05.280 --> 00:03:08.260 align:middle line:84%
And I had what I would
call the four F's.

00:03:08.260 --> 00:03:13.270 align:middle line:84%
I was frazzled,
frumpy, fat, and you

00:03:13.270 --> 00:03:14.780 align:middle line:84%
can imagine what
the fourth F was.

00:03:14.780 --> 00:03:16.320 align:middle line:90%
I was not happy.

00:03:16.320 --> 00:03:20.750 align:middle line:84%
And I had PMS, I
had low sex drive.

00:03:20.750 --> 00:03:23.592 align:middle line:90%
I felt too young to feel so old.

00:03:23.592 --> 00:03:25.300 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Did you have
kids by this time?

00:03:25.300 --> 00:03:25.725 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: I did

00:03:25.725 --> 00:03:26.308 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Wow.

00:03:26.308 --> 00:03:28.420 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: So I had
two kids in my 30s.

00:03:28.420 --> 00:03:29.450 align:middle line:90%
I have two daughters.

00:03:29.450 --> 00:03:32.990 align:middle line:84%
And honestly,
residency training was

00:03:32.990 --> 00:03:35.977 align:middle line:90%
nothing compared to being a mom.

00:03:35.977 --> 00:03:37.060 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: And it's brutal.

00:03:37.060 --> 00:03:37.675 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: It's brutal.

00:03:37.675 --> 00:03:38.500 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Brutal hours.

00:03:38.500 --> 00:03:40.249 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: And we
don't talk about that.

00:03:40.249 --> 00:03:43.130 align:middle line:84%
At least in residency, when I
was working 120 hours a week

00:03:43.130 --> 00:03:45.020 align:middle line:84%
and I was on call
every third night,

00:03:45.020 --> 00:03:47.540 align:middle line:84%
I had two nights
where I could sleep.

00:03:47.540 --> 00:03:50.040 align:middle line:84%
And when you're a mom and
you step into that role,

00:03:50.040 --> 00:03:53.820 align:middle line:84%
and we're wired as
women to over-provide,

00:03:53.820 --> 00:03:56.260 align:middle line:84%
to over-accommodate,
to people please.

00:03:56.260 --> 00:03:58.310 align:middle line:84%
So for me, when I
became a mother,

00:03:58.310 --> 00:04:00.620 align:middle line:90%
that was a pivotal time.

00:04:00.620 --> 00:04:03.480 align:middle line:90%
And I was such a stress case.

00:04:03.480 --> 00:04:04.620 align:middle line:90%
Terrible PMS.

00:04:04.620 --> 00:04:07.090 align:middle line:84%
Blamed my husband for most
things, especially in the week

00:04:07.090 --> 00:04:08.650 align:middle line:90%
before my period.

00:04:08.650 --> 00:04:10.810 align:middle line:90%
And I went to my doctor.

00:04:10.810 --> 00:04:13.040 align:middle line:90%
I did what a lot of women do.

00:04:13.040 --> 00:04:16.399 align:middle line:84%
When I saw my doctor, and
I explained my symptoms,

00:04:16.399 --> 00:04:19.110 align:middle line:84%
he wrote a prescription
for an antidepressant.

00:04:19.110 --> 00:04:25.110 align:middle line:84%
So he offered me Prozac, told me
to exercise more and eat less.

00:04:25.110 --> 00:04:28.600 align:middle line:84%
And I really felt like this
was exactly the wrong advice.

00:04:28.600 --> 00:04:32.590 align:middle line:84%
So I was able to have
that moment where

00:04:32.590 --> 00:04:36.970 align:middle line:84%
I realized OK, this legacy
from my great-grandmother, it's

00:04:36.970 --> 00:04:38.490 align:middle line:90%
coming in.

00:04:38.490 --> 00:04:40.620 align:middle line:84%
And I took that
prescription, which

00:04:40.620 --> 00:04:44.780 align:middle line:84%
just left me feeling
cold, and I decided

00:04:44.780 --> 00:04:46.720 align:middle line:84%
that I needed to apply
that medical training

00:04:46.720 --> 00:04:48.820 align:middle line:90%
to my own body.

00:04:48.820 --> 00:04:51.725 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And at that
time, were you a surgeon?

00:04:51.725 --> 00:04:52.516 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: I was.

00:04:52.516 --> 00:04:54.840 align:middle line:84%
I was board-certified
as an OB/GYN.

00:04:54.840 --> 00:04:56.530 align:middle line:84%
I'm still board-certified
as an OB/GYN,

00:04:56.530 --> 00:05:01.060 align:middle line:84%
although my focus is really on
hormones and self-realization,

00:05:01.060 --> 00:05:01.940 align:middle line:90%
really.

00:05:01.940 --> 00:05:06.170 align:middle line:84%
But at that time, I was
doing hysterectomies

00:05:06.170 --> 00:05:09.310 align:middle line:84%
during the day, prescribing
birth control pills-- which

00:05:09.310 --> 00:05:11.360 align:middle line:84%
I no longer think
is a good idea--

00:05:11.360 --> 00:05:14.470 align:middle line:84%
and I was delivering
babies at night.

00:05:14.470 --> 00:05:16.130 align:middle line:84%
I was burning the
candle at both ends.

00:05:16.130 --> 00:05:17.270 align:middle line:90%
This is not a unique story.

00:05:17.270 --> 00:05:20.470 align:middle line:84%
So many women are
experiencing this.

00:05:20.470 --> 00:05:24.520 align:middle line:84%
And when I decided to take
a look at my own hormones,

00:05:24.520 --> 00:05:28.480 align:middle line:84%
when I did what we call here in
the Silicon Valley biohacking,

00:05:28.480 --> 00:05:31.830 align:middle line:84%
and really take on my own
physiology, and figure out,

00:05:31.830 --> 00:05:34.340 align:middle line:90%
OK, why do I feel like crap?

00:05:34.340 --> 00:05:36.360 align:middle line:90%
Couldn't I do this differently?

00:05:36.360 --> 00:05:39.210 align:middle line:84%
What I found was that my
cortisol, my main stress

00:05:39.210 --> 00:05:40.610 align:middle line:90%
hormone, was sky high.

00:05:40.610 --> 00:05:44.540 align:middle line:84%
It was three times the normal
range, the optimal range.

00:05:44.540 --> 00:05:48.710 align:middle line:84%
And that was not something
that my conventional physician

00:05:48.710 --> 00:05:50.850 align:middle line:90%
would ever test for me.

00:05:50.850 --> 00:05:52.510 align:middle line:84%
So that's what got
me to start thinking

00:05:52.510 --> 00:05:55.570 align:middle line:84%
about a different way of
approaching the hormonal issues

00:05:55.570 --> 00:05:56.700 align:middle line:90%
that women have.

00:05:56.700 --> 00:05:58.940 align:middle line:84%
And I don't want to be
overly reductionistic

00:05:58.940 --> 00:06:02.450 align:middle line:84%
and say that all the problems
we face as women and men

00:06:02.450 --> 00:06:03.660 align:middle line:90%
are hormonal.

00:06:03.660 --> 00:06:04.880 align:middle line:90%
But they're a big part of it.

00:06:04.880 --> 00:06:06.671 align:middle line:84%
They really drive what
we're interested in.

00:06:06.671 --> 00:06:09.060 align:middle line:84%
The drive our
metabolism, and our mood,

00:06:09.060 --> 00:06:10.690 align:middle line:84%
and whether we have
sugar cravings.

00:06:10.690 --> 00:06:14.140 align:middle line:84%
They drive a lot of our
quality of life day to day.

00:06:14.140 --> 00:06:16.690 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So if you
take our lives back,

00:06:16.690 --> 00:06:20.280 align:middle line:84%
say, maybe five or
six decades, which

00:06:20.280 --> 00:06:22.562 align:middle line:84%
had a different set
of stressors to it.

00:06:22.562 --> 00:06:23.270 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: Yes.

00:06:23.270 --> 00:06:26.390 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But say you're a
woman, say you're a mother.

00:06:26.390 --> 00:06:28.310 align:middle line:84%
Your husband is
selling something

00:06:28.310 --> 00:06:30.890 align:middle line:84%
or he's going to work somewhere,
and you have a few kids

00:06:30.890 --> 00:06:31.390 align:middle line:90%
to raise.

00:06:31.390 --> 00:06:33.230 align:middle line:84%
And you're making
cakes in the afternoon

00:06:33.230 --> 00:06:34.750 align:middle line:84%
for when they come
home, and you're

00:06:34.750 --> 00:06:39.680 align:middle line:84%
washing your clothing by hand,
and the way of life then,

00:06:39.680 --> 00:06:44.880 align:middle line:84%
what would a cortisol
profile look like then?

00:06:44.880 --> 00:06:47.570 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: Such
a juicy question.

00:06:47.570 --> 00:06:49.080 align:middle line:84%
So the way that I
would answer that

00:06:49.080 --> 00:06:50.880 align:middle line:90%
is to start first with the data.

00:06:50.880 --> 00:06:52.820 align:middle line:84%
And then maybe fill
in some of the theory,

00:06:52.820 --> 00:06:56.490 align:middle line:84%
based on what I know from
observing women and men for 20

00:06:56.490 --> 00:06:57.770 align:middle line:90%
years.

00:06:57.770 --> 00:06:59.760 align:middle line:84%
First, we know from
studies that have

00:06:59.760 --> 00:07:03.880 align:middle line:84%
been done that women are less
happy now than they've ever

00:07:03.880 --> 00:07:06.360 align:middle line:84%
been in the history
of the world.

00:07:06.360 --> 00:07:08.150 align:middle line:90%
And I'm a feminist.

00:07:08.150 --> 00:07:14.040 align:middle line:84%
I really believe that women
bring so much value and so many

00:07:14.040 --> 00:07:17.990 align:middle line:84%
important things to the table
when it comes to equality.

00:07:17.990 --> 00:07:23.860 align:middle line:84%
And I'm a big fan of women
stepping into their power.

00:07:23.860 --> 00:07:25.900 align:middle line:84%
At the same time, I
really feel like there's

00:07:25.900 --> 00:07:28.550 align:middle line:90%
a cost to the women's movement.

00:07:28.550 --> 00:07:31.740 align:middle line:84%
So dialing back
60 to 70 years, I

00:07:31.740 --> 00:07:33.790 align:middle line:84%
would say that my
great-grandmother, who

00:07:33.790 --> 00:07:37.780 align:middle line:84%
was a bit of a
radical, she did not

00:07:37.780 --> 00:07:41.720 align:middle line:84%
have the cortisol
issues that I have.

00:07:41.720 --> 00:07:46.980 align:middle line:84%
She was not trying to raise
her children in a city

00:07:46.980 --> 00:07:49.597 align:middle line:84%
where she didn't have
any other family.

00:07:49.597 --> 00:07:50.930 align:middle line:90%
I think that's a big part of it.

00:07:50.930 --> 00:07:52.763 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: That's a big--
the whole breakdown

00:07:52.763 --> 00:07:54.600 align:middle line:90%
of family and extended family.

00:07:54.600 --> 00:07:55.342 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, absolutely.

00:07:55.342 --> 00:07:56.050 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: Yes.

00:07:56.050 --> 00:07:58.250 align:middle line:84%
We know that Hillary
Clinton famously

00:07:58.250 --> 00:08:00.810 align:middle line:84%
said it takes a village
to raise a child.

00:08:00.810 --> 00:08:03.100 align:middle line:84%
And I would say, as a
woman in perimenopause,

00:08:03.100 --> 00:08:06.540 align:middle line:84%
that it takes a village
to do most things.

00:08:06.540 --> 00:08:10.130 align:middle line:84%
Yes, for sure, with raising a
child, but many of the things

00:08:10.130 --> 00:08:11.890 align:middle line:84%
that we are trying
to do as women.

00:08:11.890 --> 00:08:13.681 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Just the
sheer comfort of knowing

00:08:13.681 --> 00:08:16.660 align:middle line:84%
you have aunts, and sisters,
and grandmothers nearby.

00:08:16.660 --> 00:08:19.070 align:middle line:84%
If your life is in
any kind of stress,

00:08:19.070 --> 00:08:20.830 align:middle line:84%
you have someone to
help share the burden.

00:08:20.830 --> 00:08:23.610 align:middle line:84%
Also to talk to, and
confide in, and trust.

00:08:23.610 --> 00:08:25.259 align:middle line:90%
Those factors aren't there.

00:08:25.259 --> 00:08:26.550 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: They're not there.

00:08:26.550 --> 00:08:31.380 align:middle line:84%
We've really lost a connection
to those intimate relationships

00:08:31.380 --> 00:08:33.460 align:middle line:90%
with our extended family.

00:08:33.460 --> 00:08:35.100 align:middle line:84%
And I think that's
an important part

00:08:35.100 --> 00:08:36.860 align:middle line:90%
of how women cope with stress.

00:08:36.860 --> 00:08:40.059 align:middle line:84%
We know that, unfortunately,
stress favors men.

00:08:40.059 --> 00:08:41.510 align:middle line:84%
And I'm saying
that as a feminist,

00:08:41.510 --> 00:08:43.780 align:middle line:84%
and it pains me a
bit to say that.

00:08:43.780 --> 00:08:46.590 align:middle line:84%
But we know that the way
that we deal with stress

00:08:46.590 --> 00:08:48.390 align:middle line:90%
is different as women.

00:08:48.390 --> 00:08:51.240 align:middle line:84%
We also, we have some
strategies that I

00:08:51.240 --> 00:08:54.110 align:middle line:84%
think are more effective than
the strategies that men use,

00:08:54.110 --> 00:08:56.820 align:middle line:84%
but not all of us are
using those strategies.

00:08:56.820 --> 00:09:02.140 align:middle line:84%
One strategy, for example,
is estrogen and oxytocin.

00:09:02.140 --> 00:09:06.120 align:middle line:84%
So we know that the classic
stress research that

00:09:06.120 --> 00:09:09.840 align:middle line:84%
was done in the 1930s by Walter
Cannon at Harvard Medical

00:09:09.840 --> 00:09:14.040 align:middle line:84%
School, he found that people
go into fight or flight

00:09:14.040 --> 00:09:16.320 align:middle line:84%
when they have a
stress response.

00:09:16.320 --> 00:09:19.290 align:middle line:84%
And that's a great system
for dealing with danger--

00:09:19.290 --> 00:09:21.740 align:middle line:84%
when you're the tiger chasing
after you, for instance.

00:09:21.740 --> 00:09:25.100 align:middle line:84%
But his research
was done in men.

00:09:25.100 --> 00:09:28.100 align:middle line:84%
And it was assumed
to apply to women.

00:09:28.100 --> 00:09:29.350 align:middle line:90%
And it doesn't apply to women.

00:09:29.350 --> 00:09:30.933 align:middle line:84%
So some women go
into fight or flight,

00:09:30.933 --> 00:09:33.000 align:middle line:84%
especially under
physical danger.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:37.050 align:middle line:84%
But when it comes
to emotional stress,

00:09:37.050 --> 00:09:38.757 align:middle line:90%
women respond very differently.

00:09:38.757 --> 00:09:39.840 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: More depression?

00:09:39.840 --> 00:09:42.640 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: Well, that's one
of the downstream effects,

00:09:42.640 --> 00:09:43.200 align:middle line:90%
I would say.

00:09:43.200 --> 00:09:45.790 align:middle line:84%
Certainly women have much
higher rates of depression,

00:09:45.790 --> 00:09:49.490 align:middle line:84%
of thyroid problems, of sleep
issues-- double the rate

00:09:49.490 --> 00:09:50.350 align:middle line:90%
of sleep issues.

00:09:50.350 --> 00:09:52.850 align:middle line:84%
We're on twice as
many antidepressants.

00:09:52.850 --> 00:09:54.570 align:middle line:90%
That's another conversation.

00:09:54.570 --> 00:09:57.380 align:middle line:84%
But when it comes to the
stress response, what

00:09:57.380 --> 00:09:59.424 align:middle line:84%
we know from some of
the research at UCLA

00:09:59.424 --> 00:10:00.840 align:middle line:84%
with Shelley Taylor,
for instance,

00:10:00.840 --> 00:10:04.090 align:middle line:90%
is that women tend and befriend.

00:10:04.090 --> 00:10:06.710 align:middle line:84%
So when you call a
girlfriend because you've

00:10:06.710 --> 00:10:10.140 align:middle line:84%
had a fight with
your darling husband,

00:10:10.140 --> 00:10:12.182 align:middle line:84%
it's a very important
hormone therapy

00:10:12.182 --> 00:10:14.140 align:middle line:84%
that you're getting when
you pick up the phone.

00:10:14.140 --> 00:10:16.430 align:middle line:90%
You are raising your oxytocin.

00:10:16.430 --> 00:10:18.492 align:middle line:84%
And a lot of people
think that oxytocin

00:10:18.492 --> 00:10:20.700 align:middle line:84%
is something that you release
when you have an orgasm

00:10:20.700 --> 00:10:22.820 align:middle line:90%
or when you breastfeed.

00:10:22.820 --> 00:10:24.400 align:middle line:84%
But it turns out
that oxytocin is

00:10:24.400 --> 00:10:27.400 align:middle line:84%
one of the most powerful
ways to lower your cortisol.

00:10:27.400 --> 00:10:29.016 align:middle line:84%
Cortisol's that
main stress hormone.

00:10:29.016 --> 00:10:30.890 align:middle line:84%
It's a little bit more
complicated than that,

00:10:30.890 --> 00:10:32.765 align:middle line:84%
but I think that's a
good way to describe it.

00:10:32.765 --> 00:10:34.780 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And you can get
it as easily as a hug.

00:10:34.780 --> 00:10:35.904 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: So a hug, yes.

00:10:35.904 --> 00:10:38.660 align:middle line:10%
There's so many different
ways to raise your oxytocin,

00:10:38.660 --> 00:10:41.244 align:middle line:10%
and one of them is hugging.

00:10:41.244 --> 00:10:43.660 align:middle line:10%
I can't remember the name of
the guy who did the Ted talk,

00:10:43.660 --> 00:10:45.909 align:middle line:10%
but he talks about
eight hugs a day,

00:10:45.909 --> 00:10:47.450 align:middle line:10%
how that's the right
dose if you look

00:10:47.450 --> 00:10:50.216 align:middle line:10%
at the physiology of oxytocin.

00:10:50.216 --> 00:10:52.590 align:middle line:84%
And by the way, you have to
hug a man a little bit longer

00:10:52.590 --> 00:10:54.360 align:middle line:84%
than you have to hug
a woman because we're

00:10:54.360 --> 00:10:56.155 align:middle line:84%
a little better at
making oxytocin.

00:10:56.155 --> 00:10:56.865 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK, OK.

00:10:56.865 --> 00:10:58.740 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: So hug your
man a little longer.

00:10:58.740 --> 00:11:01.031 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Takes them longer
to get the buzz, all right.

00:11:01.031 --> 00:11:01.830 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: Yes.

00:11:01.830 --> 00:11:03.570 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: That's interesting.

00:11:03.570 --> 00:11:04.070 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:11:04.070 --> 00:11:05.780 align:middle line:90%
So continue on with that.

00:11:05.780 --> 00:11:09.870 align:middle line:84%
So the way that our
bodies handled stress then

00:11:09.870 --> 00:11:13.880 align:middle line:84%
might look like what compared
to what we're now experiencing

00:11:13.880 --> 00:11:15.742 align:middle line:84%
in the modern
lifestyle of today.

00:11:15.742 --> 00:11:17.200 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: Well,
there's a number

00:11:17.200 --> 00:11:18.241 align:middle line:90%
of different differences.

00:11:18.241 --> 00:11:20.060 align:middle line:84%
And I think it might
be worthwhile to take

00:11:20.060 --> 00:11:21.970 align:middle line:90%
on a few of these individually.

00:11:21.970 --> 00:11:25.020 align:middle line:84%
Another huge change since
six or seven decades ago

00:11:25.020 --> 00:11:27.580 align:middle line:90%
is the food that we're eating.

00:11:27.580 --> 00:11:29.909 align:middle line:84%
Michael Pollan has
talked about how

00:11:29.909 --> 00:11:31.450 align:middle line:84%
if you're confused
about what to eat,

00:11:31.450 --> 00:11:33.717 align:middle line:84%
just eat what your
great-grandparents ate, right?

00:11:33.717 --> 00:11:34.925 align:middle line:90%
That makes such a difference.

00:11:34.925 --> 00:11:35.680 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: That's true.

00:11:35.680 --> 00:11:36.471 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: Right?

00:11:36.471 --> 00:11:37.190 align:middle line:90%
Eat whole foods.

00:11:37.190 --> 00:11:38.850 align:middle line:90%
Eat pastured milk.

00:11:38.850 --> 00:11:41.810 align:middle line:84%
Eat eggs that are not from
stressed-out chickens,

00:11:41.810 --> 00:11:44.380 align:middle line:84%
but from chickens
that are happy.

00:11:44.380 --> 00:11:46.890 align:middle line:84%
So I really believe
that the food industry

00:11:46.890 --> 00:11:48.220 align:middle line:90%
has changed dramatically.

00:11:48.220 --> 00:11:50.600 align:middle line:84%
There's so many
reasons for that.

00:11:50.600 --> 00:11:55.380 align:middle line:84%
The cow that you get at Safeway
is very different than the cow

00:11:55.380 --> 00:11:57.370 align:middle line:84%
that my great-grandmother
was eating

00:11:57.370 --> 00:11:58.822 align:middle line:90%
six or seven decades ago.

00:11:58.822 --> 00:12:00.280 align:middle line:84%
It's one of the
reasons why we have

00:12:00.280 --> 00:12:03.460 align:middle line:84%
a much higher rate of dairy
allergy, for instance.

00:12:03.460 --> 00:12:07.190 align:middle line:84%
We know that gluten has
dramatically changed.

00:12:07.190 --> 00:12:11.160 align:middle line:84%
And the way that my
grandmother ate bread,

00:12:11.160 --> 00:12:13.890 align:middle line:90%
it was often made by hand.

00:12:13.890 --> 00:12:16.860 align:middle line:84%
There's almost a meditative
quality to making bread.

00:12:16.860 --> 00:12:18.585 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Maybe
locally milled grain.

00:12:18.585 --> 00:12:20.060 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: Locally
milled grain.

00:12:20.060 --> 00:12:24.640 align:middle line:84%
And what we have now is
bread that has bromide in it,

00:12:24.640 --> 00:12:28.100 align:middle line:84%
which causes a number of
problems with your thyroid.

00:12:28.100 --> 00:12:32.250 align:middle line:84%
It has a form of gluten
that is inflammatory.

00:12:32.250 --> 00:12:33.880 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: To create
fluffy white bread.

00:12:33.880 --> 00:12:36.700 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: Fluffy white bread.

00:12:36.700 --> 00:12:39.995 align:middle line:84%
There's a big difference in
terms of the food industry.

00:12:39.995 --> 00:12:42.590 align:middle line:84%
I don't want to get on a
soapbox about just that.

00:12:42.590 --> 00:12:46.140 align:middle line:84%
But we've got all
these different drivers

00:12:46.140 --> 00:12:49.080 align:middle line:90%
of inflammation.

00:12:49.080 --> 00:12:51.519 align:middle line:84%
Cortisol's one of them,
being more stressed.

00:12:51.519 --> 00:12:53.310 align:middle line:84%
My great-grandmother
didn't have an iPhone,

00:12:53.310 --> 00:12:55.804 align:middle line:84%
for instance, which is a
blessing and curse, right?

00:12:55.804 --> 00:12:56.470 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:12:56.470 --> 00:12:58.094 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: I can
do GPS for the Soul,

00:12:58.094 --> 00:13:01.430 align:middle line:84%
and I can actually monitor
my stress response now.

00:13:01.430 --> 00:13:03.620 align:middle line:84%
But my grandmother
didn't need to do

00:13:03.620 --> 00:13:06.756 align:middle line:84%
that six or seven
decades ago like I do.

00:13:06.756 --> 00:13:08.880 align:middle line:84%
And she didn't have someone
texting her and calling

00:13:08.880 --> 00:13:11.180 align:middle line:90%
her the way that I do.

00:13:11.180 --> 00:13:13.730 align:middle line:84%
So women, I think,
are more overwhelmed.

00:13:13.730 --> 00:13:16.400 align:middle line:84%
I think we have an
epidemic of women

00:13:16.400 --> 00:13:20.060 align:middle line:84%
who feel stressed
out and overwhelmed.

00:13:20.060 --> 00:13:23.510 align:middle line:84%
Maybe a little chubbier
than they want.

00:13:23.510 --> 00:13:25.540 align:middle line:90%
More mood issues.

00:13:25.540 --> 00:13:27.980 align:middle line:84%
And the root of it
is hormone imbalance.

00:13:27.980 --> 00:13:29.480 align:middle line:84%
And if you learn
nothing else today,

00:13:29.480 --> 00:13:31.980 align:middle line:84%
but that's a really
important message, I think.

00:13:31.980 --> 00:13:36.610 align:middle line:84%
That it's not you,
it's your hormones.

00:13:36.610 --> 00:13:40.180 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: Which you address in
great detail, every hormone,

00:13:40.180 --> 00:13:45.320 align:middle line:10%
every way to approach it in
a natural way, in your book.

00:13:45.320 --> 00:13:46.820 align:middle line:10%
You've done a
beautiful job of that.

00:13:46.820 --> 00:13:49.570 align:middle line:10%
We're going to get into some
of the really key hormones

00:13:49.570 --> 00:13:52.000 align:middle line:10%
and how you can manage them
naturally rather than go

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:54.634 align:middle line:10%
get a pill for your depression.

00:13:54.634 --> 00:13:56.050 align:middle line:84%
And one thing
you're talking about

00:13:56.050 --> 00:14:00.810 align:middle line:84%
is I'm noticing among women
more and more, as time goes on,

00:14:00.810 --> 00:14:03.122 align:middle line:84%
there's a kind of
hypervigilance going on now.

00:14:03.122 --> 00:14:03.830 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: Yes.

00:14:03.830 --> 00:14:05.705 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I don't know
any other word for it.

00:14:05.705 --> 00:14:08.969 align:middle line:84%
It's like you're on alert all
the time, watching over this,

00:14:08.969 --> 00:14:09.760 align:middle line:90%
watching over that.

00:14:09.760 --> 00:14:11.260 align:middle line:84%
Making sure it all
comes together,

00:14:11.260 --> 00:14:13.860 align:middle line:84%
the house, the home, the
kids, the commuting, whatever,

00:14:13.860 --> 00:14:16.230 align:middle line:90%
comes together.

00:14:16.230 --> 00:14:19.490 align:middle line:84%
That seems to me to be one
of the greatest stressors,

00:14:19.490 --> 00:14:22.014 align:middle line:90%
is the mind never just relaxes.

00:14:22.014 --> 00:14:23.680 align:middle line:84%
You go to bed, you're
running your list.

00:14:23.680 --> 00:14:26.000 align:middle line:84%
You wake up, you have
a list waiting for you.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:27.760 align:middle line:90%
Now, this affects men too.

00:14:27.760 --> 00:14:29.950 align:middle line:84%
But we know that women
tend to multitask and take

00:14:29.950 --> 00:14:32.090 align:middle line:84%
on more responsibility
when it comes

00:14:32.090 --> 00:14:34.570 align:middle line:84%
to the domestic and
child-rearing aspects

00:14:34.570 --> 00:14:35.320 align:middle line:90%
in general.

00:14:35.320 --> 00:14:37.527 align:middle line:84%
So of course, more
hypervigilance.

00:14:37.527 --> 00:14:39.360 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: Definitely
more hypervigilance.

00:14:39.360 --> 00:14:42.052 align:middle line:90%
You're absolutely right.

00:14:42.052 --> 00:14:43.510 align:middle line:84%
If you look at the
nervous system--

00:14:43.510 --> 00:14:45.550 align:middle line:84%
I like to make this
astonishingly easy

00:14:45.550 --> 00:14:48.010 align:middle line:84%
because you can have your eyes
glaze over pretty fast when

00:14:48.010 --> 00:14:50.770 align:middle line:84%
you're talking about
biochemistry or genetics,

00:14:50.770 --> 00:14:53.080 align:middle line:84%
and how it interacts
with the environment.

00:14:53.080 --> 00:14:55.010 align:middle line:84%
So when it comes to
the nervous system,

00:14:55.010 --> 00:14:56.509 align:middle line:84%
the way that I think
about it really

00:14:56.509 --> 00:14:59.340 align:middle line:84%
simply is that you've
got an on button

00:14:59.340 --> 00:15:00.940 align:middle line:90%
and you've got an off button.

00:15:00.940 --> 00:15:03.620 align:middle line:84%
The on button is the
sympathetic nervous system.

00:15:03.620 --> 00:15:06.947 align:middle line:84%
It's what it allows
us to deal with, say,

00:15:06.947 --> 00:15:10.110 align:middle line:84%
the alarm that
went off in my home

00:15:10.110 --> 00:15:13.500 align:middle line:84%
on Saturday night when my
husband was out of town.

00:15:13.500 --> 00:15:17.120 align:middle line:84%
And when that alarm went off,
I went into hypervigilance.

00:15:17.120 --> 00:15:20.801 align:middle line:84%
I could feel my cortisol
going through the roof.

00:15:20.801 --> 00:15:23.300 align:middle line:84%
I was certain that there was a
robber or something happening

00:15:23.300 --> 00:15:24.060 align:middle line:90%
upstairs.

00:15:24.060 --> 00:15:25.590 align:middle line:90%
I had my two daughters here.

00:15:25.590 --> 00:15:27.290 align:middle line:90%
I felt really vulnerable.

00:15:27.290 --> 00:15:31.460 align:middle line:84%
It's not the best situation
for me as a woman.

00:15:31.460 --> 00:15:35.600 align:middle line:84%
The female matrix doesn't do
that well being the protector.

00:15:35.600 --> 00:15:37.800 align:middle line:84%
When my husband's here,
and he's lying by my side,

00:15:37.800 --> 00:15:38.860 align:middle line:90%
and the alarm goes off?

00:15:38.860 --> 00:15:40.870 align:middle line:90%
I don't have that same response.

00:15:40.870 --> 00:15:43.610 align:middle line:84%
I can actually go back to
bed after he goes and deals

00:15:43.610 --> 00:15:44.650 align:middle line:90%
with it.

00:15:44.650 --> 00:15:47.030 align:middle line:84%
So you're absolutely right
about this hypervigilance.

00:15:47.030 --> 00:15:50.300 align:middle line:84%
We are really good
at this on button.

00:15:50.300 --> 00:15:53.170 align:middle line:84%
We're not so good
at the off button.

00:15:53.170 --> 00:15:56.110 align:middle line:84%
So the off button is the
parasympathetic nervous system.

00:15:56.110 --> 00:15:58.640 align:middle line:84%
And we want this lovely
dance between the two,

00:15:58.640 --> 00:16:02.240 align:middle line:84%
like a tango, where
you're not in hyperdrive,

00:16:02.240 --> 00:16:05.100 align:middle line:84%
you're not constantly
pushing that on button.

00:16:05.100 --> 00:16:09.105 align:middle line:84%
Most of us are like race
car drivers, I think.

00:16:09.105 --> 00:16:11.380 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to give you a male
analogy, how about that?

00:16:11.380 --> 00:16:14.280 align:middle line:84%
So I think of race
car drivers, I

00:16:14.280 --> 00:16:17.540 align:middle line:84%
think about how
their mastery doesn't

00:16:17.540 --> 00:16:21.050 align:middle line:84%
come from pressing the
pedal to the metal.

00:16:21.050 --> 00:16:24.050 align:middle line:84%
It comes from knowing when
to take a strategic break.

00:16:24.050 --> 00:16:27.020 align:middle line:84%
It comes from figuring
out I need a pit stop.

00:16:27.020 --> 00:16:28.720 align:middle line:90%
I need some new tires.

00:16:28.720 --> 00:16:32.050 align:middle line:84%
I need to know when to hit the
pause button so that I really

00:16:32.050 --> 00:16:36.000 align:middle line:84%
have mastery around my
success as a race car driver.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:38.770 align:middle line:84%
So we've got to really focus
on that off button, something

00:16:38.770 --> 00:16:40.570 align:middle line:84%
that I think you've
done so beautifully,

00:16:40.570 --> 00:16:42.320 align:middle line:90%
Regina, in your career.

00:16:42.320 --> 00:16:46.090 align:middle line:84%
So I feel like when I have a
woman who comes and sees me

00:16:46.090 --> 00:16:49.910 align:middle line:84%
in my practice--
and I'll tell you

00:16:49.910 --> 00:16:52.270 align:middle line:90%
about one that I saw this week.

00:16:52.270 --> 00:16:57.540 align:middle line:84%
I have a woman named
Joan, who is 47 years old.

00:16:57.540 --> 00:17:02.780 align:middle line:84%
And she came to me and she said,
"I would rather do anything

00:17:02.780 --> 00:17:04.960 align:middle line:90%
than have sex with my husband.

00:17:04.960 --> 00:17:07.420 align:middle line:90%
I would rather be on Facebook.

00:17:07.420 --> 00:17:08.250 align:middle line:90%
I'd rather garden.

00:17:08.250 --> 00:17:10.270 align:middle line:90%
I'd rather drink a smoothie.

00:17:10.270 --> 00:17:11.770 align:middle line:90%
And it's affecting our marriage.

00:17:11.770 --> 00:17:12.990 align:middle line:90%
I feel really bad about it.

00:17:12.990 --> 00:17:14.859 align:middle line:90%
I love my husband.

00:17:14.859 --> 00:17:17.579 align:middle line:84%
But I feel like I am
such as stress case.

00:17:17.579 --> 00:17:20.420 align:middle line:84%
I'm running around,
task to task,

00:17:20.420 --> 00:17:24.702 align:middle line:84%
not able to slow down and
enjoy sex with my husband.

00:17:24.702 --> 00:17:26.785 align:middle line:84%
Can't you just give you
some of that testosterone?

00:17:26.785 --> 00:17:28.950 align:middle line:84%
I heard testosterone
would help."

00:17:28.950 --> 00:17:32.470 align:middle line:84%
So here again, she's talking
about a bioidentical hormone,

00:17:32.470 --> 00:17:35.730 align:middle line:84%
but she's jumping
to the prescription.

00:17:35.730 --> 00:17:38.810 align:middle line:84%
And I think it's so
important to look at,

00:17:38.810 --> 00:17:42.000 align:middle line:84%
upstream, what are
the root causes.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:43.730 align:middle line:84%
Because when you
find the root cause

00:17:43.730 --> 00:17:46.790 align:middle line:84%
rather than being in a
rush to mask the symptom,

00:17:46.790 --> 00:17:49.100 align:middle line:84%
that's where you're more
likely to have a cure.

00:17:49.100 --> 00:17:52.590 align:middle line:84%
You're more likely to create
this good neighborhood.

00:17:52.590 --> 00:17:55.290 align:middle line:84%
So what we found with her
was that her cortisol,

00:17:55.290 --> 00:17:59.630 align:middle line:84%
similar to mine in my 30s,
was quite high in the morning.

00:17:59.630 --> 00:18:01.960 align:middle line:84%
And then it was quite
low in the afternoon.

00:18:01.960 --> 00:18:05.270 align:middle line:84%
And it made her have this
brain fog, like low energy

00:18:05.270 --> 00:18:06.570 align:middle line:90%
in the afternoon.

00:18:06.570 --> 00:18:08.650 align:middle line:84%
And so what we
figured out was a way

00:18:08.650 --> 00:18:12.060 align:middle line:84%
to manage her cortisol
so that we could get it

00:18:12.060 --> 00:18:14.030 align:middle line:84%
into that Goldilocks
position in the morning.

00:18:14.030 --> 00:18:14.870 align:middle line:90%
Not too high.

00:18:14.870 --> 00:18:17.204 align:middle line:84%
Not that tired, but
wired stress feeling

00:18:17.204 --> 00:18:18.620 align:middle line:84%
where you're
hypervigilant, right?

00:18:18.620 --> 00:18:20.430 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: A terrible
feeling, yeah.

00:18:20.430 --> 00:18:22.763 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: And then in the
afternoon when she has that

00:18:22.763 --> 00:18:25.090 align:middle line:84%
brain fog and she's
reaching for, I don't know--

00:18:25.090 --> 00:18:25.840 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: A mocha.

00:18:25.840 --> 00:18:28.050 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: --a
latte, chocolate,

00:18:28.050 --> 00:18:33.110 align:middle line:84%
anything-- what we did there
is we actually had her start

00:18:33.110 --> 00:18:35.630 align:middle line:84%
doing a form of exercise
that would help her

00:18:35.630 --> 00:18:37.692 align:middle line:84%
with her cortisol levels
and reduce the sugar

00:18:37.692 --> 00:18:38.900 align:middle line:90%
cravings that she was having.

00:18:38.900 --> 00:18:42.820 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And that's really
key because all exercise is not

00:18:42.820 --> 00:18:43.755 align:middle line:90%
equal.

00:18:43.755 --> 00:18:44.140 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: Absolutely.

00:18:44.140 --> 00:18:46.264 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Especially
depending on your own profile.

00:18:46.264 --> 00:18:49.640 align:middle line:84%
Some are jacking up cortisol
and some are soothing it, right?

00:18:49.640 --> 00:18:52.450 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: So true, and I
think we don't realize this.

00:18:52.450 --> 00:18:55.120 align:middle line:84%
We've got this idea
that one size fits

00:18:55.120 --> 00:18:57.850 align:middle line:84%
all when it comes to
our health, and nothing

00:18:57.850 --> 00:18:59.360 align:middle line:90%
could be further from the truth.

00:18:59.360 --> 00:19:02.244 align:middle line:84%
We've really got to figure out
how do we calibrate for you.

00:19:02.244 --> 00:19:03.910 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So what
happened to this lady?

00:19:03.910 --> 00:19:05.630 align:middle line:84%
So you get her on
appropriate exercise

00:19:05.630 --> 00:19:08.350 align:middle line:84%
in the middle of the
afternoon instead of caffeine.

00:19:08.350 --> 00:19:10.720 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: So we
changed her cortisol.

00:19:10.720 --> 00:19:13.640 align:middle line:84%
And the cool part
here is that when

00:19:13.640 --> 00:19:16.790 align:middle line:84%
you change the root cause,
and her high cortisol

00:19:16.790 --> 00:19:19.720 align:middle line:84%
in the morning, low cortisol
in the afternoon, what we found

00:19:19.720 --> 00:19:24.340 align:middle line:84%
was that we were able to get
her other hormones into balance.

00:19:24.340 --> 00:19:26.550 align:middle line:84%
So in her situation,
she had what

00:19:26.550 --> 00:19:30.290 align:middle line:84%
I would call a problem with
hormonal Charlie's Angels.

00:19:30.290 --> 00:19:31.290 align:middle line:90%
Can I mention that, too?

00:19:31.290 --> 00:19:33.106 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Sure.

00:19:33.106 --> 00:19:36.530 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: When I was
going through this biohacking

00:19:36.530 --> 00:19:38.710 align:middle line:84%
exercise in my
30s, and I realized

00:19:38.710 --> 00:19:39.980 align:middle line:90%
that my cortisol was high.

00:19:39.980 --> 00:19:42.940 align:middle line:84%
And one of the reasons
why I was gaining weight

00:19:42.940 --> 00:19:45.370 align:middle line:84%
was because my thyroid
wasn't working well.

00:19:45.370 --> 00:19:46.670 align:middle line:90%
It was low.

00:19:46.670 --> 00:19:48.180 align:middle line:90%
I also had estrogen dominance.

00:19:48.180 --> 00:19:51.950 align:middle line:84%
I had pretty much every problem
a woman could have, hormonally.

00:19:51.950 --> 00:19:54.700 align:middle line:90%
And I came to this conclusion.

00:19:54.700 --> 00:19:59.080 align:middle line:84%
I had another epiphany, which
is that you want three hormones

00:19:59.080 --> 00:20:02.155 align:middle line:90%
in particular to support you.

00:20:02.155 --> 00:20:03.530 align:middle line:84%
And this is another
place where I

00:20:03.530 --> 00:20:06.140 align:middle line:84%
love to keep it
astonishingly simple.

00:20:06.140 --> 00:20:07.990 align:middle line:84%
These are your hormonal
Charlie's Angels.

00:20:07.990 --> 00:20:11.910 align:middle line:84%
They are cortisol,
estrogen, and thyroid.

00:20:11.910 --> 00:20:15.050 align:middle line:84%
In men, I like to always give
the men a little something

00:20:15.050 --> 00:20:15.760 align:middle line:90%
to think about.

00:20:15.760 --> 00:20:17.260 align:middle line:84%
In men, it's a
little bit different.

00:20:17.260 --> 00:20:20.540 align:middle line:84%
It's cortisol,
testosterone, thyroid.

00:20:20.540 --> 00:20:23.250 align:middle line:84%
If you have those three
hormones working for you, not

00:20:23.250 --> 00:20:26.912 align:middle line:84%
against you, you are going to
be able to feel so much better.

00:20:26.912 --> 00:20:28.370 align:middle line:84%
Like you're living
life fully, like

00:20:28.370 --> 00:20:29.995 align:middle line:84%
you're able to rock
your mission and be

00:20:29.995 --> 00:20:33.180 align:middle line:90%
of service in a whole new way.

00:20:33.180 --> 00:20:36.000 align:middle line:84%
So what we did with this woman
was we worked on the cortisol.

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:38.210 align:middle line:84%
That actually
helped her thyroid.

00:20:38.210 --> 00:20:40.220 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yes, because
the two are intertwined.

00:20:40.220 --> 00:20:41.636 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: They
are intertwined.

00:20:41.636 --> 00:20:43.990 align:middle line:84%
When one goes up,
the other goes down.

00:20:43.990 --> 00:20:47.130 align:middle line:84%
And thyroid has a lot
of important roles.

00:20:47.130 --> 00:20:49.520 align:middle line:84%
We know that 20% of
people with depression

00:20:49.520 --> 00:20:51.540 align:middle line:90%
have low thyroid function.

00:20:51.540 --> 00:20:54.510 align:middle line:84%
And it makes me crazy when
someone comes to see me.

00:20:54.510 --> 00:20:56.560 align:middle line:84%
They get started on
an antidepressant

00:20:56.560 --> 00:20:58.680 align:middle line:84%
and no one ever
checked their thyroid.

00:20:58.680 --> 00:21:00.760 align:middle line:90%
So we want to think about that.

00:21:00.760 --> 00:21:03.260 align:middle line:84%
The other piece for
her is that her thyroid

00:21:03.260 --> 00:21:06.320 align:middle line:84%
was a big part of
her low sex drive.

00:21:06.320 --> 00:21:10.240 align:middle line:84%
So she had hypervigilance,
low thyroid function,

00:21:10.240 --> 00:21:11.350 align:middle line:90%
and she was 47.

00:21:11.350 --> 00:21:13.450 align:middle line:84%
So she was right
at that age where

00:21:13.450 --> 00:21:15.840 align:middle line:84%
I think about it as a
perfect storm, where

00:21:15.840 --> 00:21:18.180 align:middle line:84%
you have a problem
with all three

00:21:18.180 --> 00:21:20.410 align:middle line:84%
of these hormonal
Charlie's Angels.

00:21:20.410 --> 00:21:22.940 align:middle line:84%
So in her situation,
her estrogen was lower.

00:21:22.940 --> 00:21:25.810 align:middle line:84%
It was causing some
vaginal dryness.

00:21:25.810 --> 00:21:27.910 align:middle line:84%
And that was part
of the reason why

00:21:27.910 --> 00:21:30.670 align:middle line:90%
she wasn't enjoying sex as much.

00:21:30.670 --> 00:21:33.590 align:middle line:90%
Her orgasms had changed.

00:21:33.590 --> 00:21:37.770 align:middle line:84%
The lining of her lady
garden, her female genitalia,

00:21:37.770 --> 00:21:39.430 align:middle line:90%
was starting to change.

00:21:39.430 --> 00:21:43.990 align:middle line:84%
Testosterone was lower
because of the high cortisol.

00:21:43.990 --> 00:21:47.800 align:middle line:84%
So when you go to the root
cause and you fix the cortisol,

00:21:47.800 --> 00:21:49.570 align:middle line:84%
the beautiful thing
is the crosstalk

00:21:49.570 --> 00:21:50.540 align:middle line:90%
between these hormones.

00:21:50.540 --> 00:21:52.414 align:middle line:84%
So when we did that,
when we got her cortisol

00:21:52.414 --> 00:21:55.600 align:middle line:84%
to support her
again, her thyroid

00:21:55.600 --> 00:21:57.680 align:middle line:90%
got into the optimal range.

00:21:57.680 --> 00:22:00.080 align:middle line:90%
Her estrogen balance got better.

00:22:00.080 --> 00:22:05.020 align:middle line:84%
We did a little bit of
local therapy in the vagina

00:22:05.020 --> 00:22:08.435 align:middle line:84%
with some bioidentical,
lowest dose estrogen.

00:22:08.435 --> 00:22:09.390 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Creams.

00:22:09.390 --> 00:22:10.400 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: And it
made a big difference

00:22:10.400 --> 00:22:11.441 align:middle line:90%
with the vaginal dryness.

00:22:11.441 --> 00:22:13.274 align:middle line:90%
It also helped her orgasms.

00:22:13.274 --> 00:22:14.190 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Interesting.

00:22:14.190 --> 00:22:14.810 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: So
one of the things

00:22:14.810 --> 00:22:16.570 align:middle line:84%
that she didn't tell
me when we first

00:22:16.570 --> 00:22:21.680 align:middle line:84%
started talking is that she
had always really enjoyed sex.

00:22:21.680 --> 00:22:25.210 align:middle line:84%
And she really enjoyed the
orgasms that she would have.

00:22:25.210 --> 00:22:28.070 align:middle line:84%
And she felt like in
her 40s, the orgasms

00:22:28.070 --> 00:22:30.080 align:middle line:90%
were just slowly fading.

00:22:30.080 --> 00:22:33.400 align:middle line:84%
They weren't toe-curling
like they were in the past,

00:22:33.400 --> 00:22:35.920 align:middle line:90%
in her 20s and in her 30s.

00:22:35.920 --> 00:22:39.830 align:middle line:84%
And she could barely even notice
if she was having an orgasm.

00:22:39.830 --> 00:22:42.650 align:middle line:84%
And part of that was
an estrogen effect.

00:22:42.650 --> 00:22:45.411 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Too much estrogen?

00:22:45.411 --> 00:22:47.410 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: It's a little
bit more complicated.

00:22:47.410 --> 00:22:49.650 align:middle line:84%
In her situation,
she was actually low

00:22:49.650 --> 00:22:52.470 align:middle line:84%
in estrogen, which is
why she had the dryness.

00:22:52.470 --> 00:22:56.680 align:middle line:84%
But you're right that just
as when I was in my 30s

00:22:56.680 --> 00:22:59.100 align:middle line:84%
and I had estrogen
dominance, which is common--

00:22:59.100 --> 00:23:04.310 align:middle line:84%
it's about 70 to 80% of women
between the ages of 35 and 45--

00:23:04.310 --> 00:23:07.690 align:middle line:84%
that's the first part
of perimenopause.

00:23:07.690 --> 00:23:09.630 align:middle line:90%
So phase one, perimenopause.

00:23:09.630 --> 00:23:12.320 align:middle line:84%
Your progesterone
is low, and you

00:23:12.320 --> 00:23:14.080 align:middle line:90%
get into estrogen dominance.

00:23:14.080 --> 00:23:15.330 align:middle line:90%
It's another tango.

00:23:15.330 --> 00:23:18.360 align:middle line:84%
You want a really nice
ratio between progesterone

00:23:18.360 --> 00:23:18.940 align:middle line:90%
and estrogen.

00:23:18.940 --> 00:23:20.520 align:middle line:90%
Estrogen's like that.

00:23:20.520 --> 00:23:22.970 align:middle line:84%
It's the archetypal
feminine hormone.

00:23:22.970 --> 00:23:25.445 align:middle line:84%
It gives us breasts,
and hips, and makes

00:23:25.445 --> 00:23:28.460 align:middle line:84%
us juicy in our
joints, in our vagina.

00:23:28.460 --> 00:23:31.670 align:middle line:84%
And progesterone is
like that stable partner

00:23:31.670 --> 00:23:32.970 align:middle line:90%
that you can really rely on.

00:23:32.970 --> 00:23:34.000 align:middle line:90%
It soothes you.

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:35.720 align:middle line:90%
You feel protected.

00:23:35.720 --> 00:23:37.570 align:middle line:90%
Protects your uterus.

00:23:37.570 --> 00:23:38.820 align:middle line:90%
Helps you calm down.

00:23:38.820 --> 00:23:40.800 align:middle line:90%
It's like nature's Valium.

00:23:40.800 --> 00:23:43.250 align:middle line:84%
And the first thing that
happens between 35 and 45

00:23:43.250 --> 00:23:46.190 align:middle line:84%
is that your ovaries don't
make as much progesterone.

00:23:46.190 --> 00:23:50.190 align:middle line:84%
And a lot of women feel this,
like it's harder to calm down.

00:23:50.190 --> 00:23:52.720 align:middle line:84%
They have that
hypervigilance, right?

00:23:52.720 --> 00:23:54.170 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: And don't sleep well.

00:23:54.170 --> 00:23:54.930 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: They
don't sleep well,

00:23:54.930 --> 00:23:56.910 align:middle line:84%
and then they get
into this spiral.

00:23:56.910 --> 00:23:59.706 align:middle line:84%
When you don't sleep well,
it raises your cortisol.

00:23:59.706 --> 00:24:01.580 align:middle line:84%
Then you start drinking
coffee in the morning

00:24:01.580 --> 00:24:02.980 align:middle line:84%
and it's all you can think
about when you wake up.

00:24:02.980 --> 00:24:05.140 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Or taking Ambien
or some drug at night.

00:24:05.140 --> 00:24:06.990 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: Or taking
a sleeping pill.

00:24:06.990 --> 00:24:09.670 align:middle line:84%
When you don't sleep well
at night, raises cortisol.

00:24:09.670 --> 00:24:12.090 align:middle line:84%
And then you start
looking for sugar,

00:24:12.090 --> 00:24:14.100 align:middle line:84%
because it can make you
have sugar cravings.

00:24:14.100 --> 00:24:16.530 align:middle line:84%
It can give you
problems with insulin.

00:24:16.530 --> 00:24:20.480 align:middle line:84%
And when insulin starts to rise,
as it does when cortisol starts

00:24:20.480 --> 00:24:24.100 align:middle line:84%
to rise, that makes you lay
down more fat, especially right

00:24:24.100 --> 00:24:26.030 align:middle line:90%
here at the muffin top.

00:24:26.030 --> 00:24:28.600 align:middle line:84%
So there's this whole
vicious cycle that happens.

00:24:28.600 --> 00:24:31.290 align:middle line:10%
And what I really want
women to understand

00:24:31.290 --> 00:24:35.440 align:middle line:10%
is that you're not
doing anything wrong.

00:24:35.440 --> 00:24:37.950 align:middle line:10%
There's probably a
biological reason

00:24:37.950 --> 00:24:41.750 align:middle line:10%
why you feel overwhelmed,
why you feel hypervigilant.

00:24:41.750 --> 00:24:45.530 align:middle line:84%
It's not a matter of
you're missing the mark.

00:24:45.530 --> 00:24:47.390 align:middle line:84%
I want you to start
with the biology.

00:24:47.390 --> 00:24:48.710 align:middle line:84%
I think that's a really
important message.

00:24:48.710 --> 00:24:49.180 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well, you've
helped thousands

00:24:49.180 --> 00:24:51.637 align:middle line:84%
of women on this level
already, haven't you?

00:24:51.637 --> 00:24:53.470 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: Well, I've
been very fortunate.

00:24:53.470 --> 00:24:58.070 align:middle line:10%
I've been seeing
patients for awhile.

00:24:58.070 --> 00:25:00.490 align:middle line:10%
I started at Harvard
Medical School in 1989.

00:25:00.490 --> 00:25:02.810 align:middle line:10%
Actually, I moved
there from Alaska.

00:25:02.810 --> 00:25:05.489 align:middle line:10%
There are not many Alaskans who
go to Harvard Medical School.

00:25:05.489 --> 00:25:06.030 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: No.

00:25:06.030 --> 00:25:06.310 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: No.

00:25:06.310 --> 00:25:08.280 align:middle line:84%
And there's even this
attitude in Alaska--

00:25:08.280 --> 00:25:13.060 align:middle line:84%
I moved from Maryland
