And that's a little
hyperbolic, but I really

00:36:31.896 --> 00:36:32.770 align:middle line:90%
think it's important.

00:36:32.770 --> 00:36:34.145 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: Sara,
every person I've

00:36:34.145 --> 00:36:37.160 align:middle line:10%
interviewed that is in
the field of natural ways

00:36:37.160 --> 00:36:39.720 align:middle line:10%
to recover our health has
said exactly the same thing

00:36:39.720 --> 00:36:41.486 align:middle line:10%
without such dramatic terms.

00:36:41.486 --> 00:36:44.170 align:middle line:10%
And which is very bad
news for sugar babies who

00:36:44.170 --> 00:36:45.820 align:middle line:10%
just love having a little sugar.

00:36:45.820 --> 00:36:47.570 align:middle line:10%
But let's talk about that.

00:36:47.570 --> 00:36:48.690 align:middle line:10%
What is it doing?

00:36:48.690 --> 00:36:51.700 align:middle line:10%
>>GOTTFRIED: Well, my heart
goes out to these people.

00:36:51.700 --> 00:36:53.550 align:middle line:10%
I used to hear
jungle drums when I

00:36:53.550 --> 00:36:57.920 align:middle line:10%
was in my 30s, when I was that
four F, stressed out, working

00:36:57.920 --> 00:36:59.000 align:middle line:10%
mom.

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:01.210 align:middle line:10%
I know what this feels
like, and I'm not

00:37:01.210 --> 00:37:04.720 align:middle line:10%
saying this with any
sort of judgment.

00:37:04.720 --> 00:37:06.690 align:middle line:84%
We've got to turn
this ship around.

00:37:06.690 --> 00:37:09.350 align:middle line:10%
So when it comes
to sugar cravings,

00:37:09.350 --> 00:37:13.220 align:middle line:10%
I just did a survey
of my community

00:37:13.220 --> 00:37:15.560 align:middle line:10%
at saragottfriedmd.com.

00:37:15.560 --> 00:37:18.280 align:middle line:10%
I've got a total
of 30,000, mostly

00:37:18.280 --> 00:37:21.920 align:middle line:10%
women, who responded to
this survey just last month.

00:37:21.920 --> 00:37:26.270 align:middle line:84%
And they told me that the top
three issues they're facing

00:37:26.270 --> 00:37:32.030 align:middle line:84%
are sugar cravings, low
or inconsistent energy,

00:37:32.030 --> 00:37:35.920 align:middle line:90%
and problems with stress.

00:37:35.920 --> 00:37:40.410 align:middle line:84%
Just feeling like they can't get
on top of the stress machine.

00:37:40.410 --> 00:37:42.410 align:middle line:84%
So those are the three
issues, and some of these

00:37:42.410 --> 00:37:43.470 align:middle line:90%
are actually conflated.

00:37:43.470 --> 00:37:46.260 align:middle line:84%
So it turns out that
cortisol is a big part

00:37:46.260 --> 00:37:48.820 align:middle line:84%
of why people have
sugar cravings.

00:37:48.820 --> 00:37:50.320 align:middle line:84%
This is actually a
really juicy one,

00:37:50.320 --> 00:37:51.260 align:middle line:84%
so maybe we could
talk about some

00:37:51.260 --> 00:37:52.630 align:middle line:84%
of the natural ways
of dealing with this.

00:37:52.630 --> 00:37:52.740 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah, let's do.

00:37:52.740 --> 00:37:53.170 align:middle line:90%
Please.

00:37:53.170 --> 00:37:55.503 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: So when you have
sugar, one of the problems

00:37:55.503 --> 00:38:00.080 align:middle line:84%
is that when you have a big
old chunk of chocolate cake--

00:38:00.080 --> 00:38:02.690 align:middle line:84%
and no one loves
chocolate like I do.

00:38:02.690 --> 00:38:06.950 align:middle line:84%
But I want you to actually
have the dark chocolate cacao.

00:38:06.950 --> 00:38:08.712 align:middle line:90%
That lowers cortisol.

00:38:08.712 --> 00:38:09.420 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Really?

00:38:09.420 --> 00:38:10.570 align:middle line:90%
The natural cacao?

00:38:10.570 --> 00:38:11.540 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: Yes.

00:38:11.540 --> 00:38:13.000 align:middle line:90%
So this is super cool.

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:15.800 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But it doesn't
taste good all by itself.

00:38:15.800 --> 00:38:19.080 align:middle line:84%
You have to sweeten it with
something to make that go down.

00:38:19.080 --> 00:38:21.690 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: So we should have
a conversation about that,

00:38:21.690 --> 00:38:22.190 align:middle line:90%
I think.

00:38:22.190 --> 00:38:22.820 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:38:22.820 --> 00:38:24.236 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: So
to me, this is one

00:38:24.236 --> 00:38:26.200 align:middle line:84%
of the most exciting
randomized trials that's

00:38:26.200 --> 00:38:28.569 align:middle line:84%
ever been done in the history
of looking at cortisol.

00:38:28.569 --> 00:38:29.360 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Fabulous.

00:38:29.360 --> 00:38:31.401 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: To show that
dark chocolate actually

00:38:31.401 --> 00:38:32.690 align:middle line:90%
lowers cortisol.

00:38:32.690 --> 00:38:34.460 align:middle line:84%
So the idea here
is that you want

00:38:34.460 --> 00:38:37.320 align:middle line:84%
to limit the amount of sugar
that's in that dark chocolate.

00:38:37.320 --> 00:38:37.920 align:middle line:90%
You're right.

00:38:37.920 --> 00:38:42.130 align:middle line:84%
Eating pure cacao is not
everyone's cup of tea.

00:38:42.130 --> 00:38:43.170 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: No.

00:38:43.170 --> 00:38:46.910 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: But if you
get a really fine, organic,

00:38:46.910 --> 00:38:53.692 align:middle line:84%
raw chocolate bar that
is 80% to 90% cacao,

00:38:53.692 --> 00:38:55.650 align:middle line:84%
that really helps you
with your cortisol level.

00:38:55.650 --> 00:38:57.456 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And that
helps lower cortisol.

00:38:57.456 --> 00:38:58.330 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: It does.

00:38:58.330 --> 00:39:00.230 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Not the study
that you talked about

00:39:00.230 --> 00:39:02.540 align:middle line:90%
by Nestle's corporation?

00:39:02.540 --> 00:39:04.247 align:middle line:90%
That was a different one.

00:39:04.247 --> 00:39:06.205 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: Well, this
is a randomized trial--

00:39:06.205 --> 00:39:06.490 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: That's wonderful.

00:39:06.490 --> 00:39:07.906 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: --that
actually shows

00:39:07.906 --> 00:39:09.580 align:middle line:90%
that dark chocolate does this.

00:39:09.580 --> 00:39:10.100 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: God, that's great.

00:39:10.100 --> 00:39:12.391 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: So we're not
talking about milk chocolate.

00:39:12.391 --> 00:39:14.750 align:middle line:84%
We're not talking about having
a ton of sugar in there.

00:39:14.750 --> 00:39:15.291 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: No.

00:39:15.291 --> 00:39:17.187 align:middle line:84%
Talking 80% and above
solid cocoa mass.

00:39:17.187 --> 00:39:18.270 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: That's right.

00:39:18.270 --> 00:39:19.110 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Cacao mass.

00:39:19.110 --> 00:39:19.240 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:39:19.240 --> 00:39:20.323 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: That's right.

00:39:20.323 --> 00:39:22.770 align:middle line:84%
So if you are eating a big
old hunk of chocolate cake

00:39:22.770 --> 00:39:26.780 align:middle line:84%
or you're choosing a doughnut,
that raises your cortisol.

00:39:26.780 --> 00:39:28.040 align:middle line:90%
So that's an interrupter.

00:39:28.040 --> 00:39:31.811 align:middle line:84%
And then along the same
continuum is actually alcohol.

00:39:31.811 --> 00:39:33.435 align:middle line:84%
Can we talk about
alcohol for a moment?

00:39:33.435 --> 00:39:33.720 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Sure.

00:39:33.720 --> 00:39:35.886 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: This is a
really important interrupter,

00:39:35.886 --> 00:39:39.650 align:middle line:84%
especially in the female body,
the female matrix that I think

00:39:39.650 --> 00:39:42.140 align:middle line:84%
of in a functional
medicine perspective.

00:39:42.140 --> 00:39:44.970 align:middle line:90%
So alcohol.

00:39:44.970 --> 00:39:48.070 align:middle line:84%
Going back to when I was in my
30s-- I think a lot of women

00:39:48.070 --> 00:39:51.520 align:middle line:84%
can relate to this-- when
I came home and was trying

00:39:51.520 --> 00:39:55.090 align:middle line:84%
to transition to being a mom,
came home for the second shift,

00:39:55.090 --> 00:39:55.630 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:39:55.630 --> 00:39:56.810 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:39:56.810 --> 00:39:59.200 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: What I
wanted more than anything

00:39:59.200 --> 00:40:01.277 align:middle line:90%
was a glass of wine.

00:40:01.277 --> 00:40:02.610 align:middle line:90%
So I would pour a glass of wine.

00:40:02.610 --> 00:40:05.530 align:middle line:84%
I'd start making dinner and
connecting with my family.

00:40:05.530 --> 00:40:08.120 align:middle line:84%
And then maybe I'd
have another glass.

00:40:08.120 --> 00:40:10.640 align:middle line:84%
And this is part of that
whole vicious cycle that

00:40:10.640 --> 00:40:14.230 align:middle line:84%
led to me gaining
weight in my 30s.

00:40:14.230 --> 00:40:17.990 align:middle line:84%
It turns out that in the female
body, the very thing that you

00:40:17.990 --> 00:40:19.660 align:middle line:84%
think you're getting
from alcohol,

00:40:19.660 --> 00:40:21.500 align:middle line:90%
it's actually robbing from you.

00:40:21.500 --> 00:40:24.370 align:middle line:84%
So you think that you're
hitting that pause

00:40:24.370 --> 00:40:25.370 align:middle line:90%
button with the alcohol.

00:40:25.370 --> 00:40:27.290 align:middle line:84%
You think that
you're calming down.

00:40:27.290 --> 00:40:29.030 align:middle line:84%
And it turns out
that the alcohol

00:40:29.030 --> 00:40:31.464 align:middle line:84%
is raising your
cortisol and disrupting

00:40:31.464 --> 00:40:32.380 align:middle line:90%
your sleep that night.

00:40:32.380 --> 00:40:33.470 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: That makes
sense because I

00:40:33.470 --> 00:40:34.469 align:middle line:90%
don't drink much at all.

00:40:34.469 --> 00:40:37.500 align:middle line:84%
I never have and when on
the rare occasion that I do,

00:40:37.500 --> 00:40:39.000 align:middle line:90%
I have the worst sleep.

00:40:39.000 --> 00:40:40.750 align:middle line:84%
And I always thought,
what's up with that?

00:40:40.750 --> 00:40:41.080 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: Yes.

00:40:41.080 --> 00:40:42.640 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So it's
raising your cortisol,

00:40:42.640 --> 00:40:44.010 align:middle line:90%
which is messing up your sleep.

00:40:44.010 --> 00:40:44.610 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: It is.

00:40:44.610 --> 00:40:45.330 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Interesting.

00:40:45.330 --> 00:40:47.204 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: I find that
most paths lead back

00:40:47.204 --> 00:40:48.430 align:middle line:90%
to cortisol, right?

00:40:48.430 --> 00:40:50.840 align:middle line:84%
Cortisol's this really
interesting hormone

00:40:50.840 --> 00:40:53.580 align:middle line:84%
that is in charge of all these
other hormones, your hormonal

00:40:53.580 --> 00:40:54.990 align:middle line:90%
Charlie's Angels.

00:40:54.990 --> 00:40:57.424 align:middle line:84%
And a lot of people,
when they have alcohol,

00:40:57.424 --> 00:41:00.090 align:middle line:84%
they'll fall asleep more easily,
but they don't have deep sleep.

00:41:00.090 --> 00:41:01.130 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: You don't
stay asleep, right.

00:41:01.130 --> 00:41:03.340 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: You don't
have high quality sleep.

00:41:03.340 --> 00:41:06.220 align:middle line:84%
The other piece that's
important for women

00:41:06.220 --> 00:41:08.480 align:middle line:84%
is that there's a new
study that came out

00:41:08.480 --> 00:41:10.820 align:middle line:84%
in 2011, in the
Nurses' Health Study,

00:41:10.820 --> 00:41:13.710 align:middle line:84%
showing that women who
have more than three

00:41:13.710 --> 00:41:16.490 align:middle line:84%
to six servings
a week of alcohol

00:41:16.490 --> 00:41:19.290 align:middle line:84%
have a greater risk
of breast cancer.

00:41:19.290 --> 00:41:22.570 align:middle line:84%
Now, this is the first time
such a small amount of alcohol

00:41:22.570 --> 00:41:25.951 align:middle line:84%
has been shown to increase
your bad estrogens.

00:41:25.951 --> 00:41:27.700 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Which makes
sense if you're also

00:41:27.700 --> 00:41:28.830 align:middle line:90%
jacking up your cortisol.

00:41:28.830 --> 00:41:31.450 align:middle line:84%
And cortisol's always
comes back as implicated

00:41:31.450 --> 00:41:33.615 align:middle line:84%
in the development of
certain cancers, right?

00:41:33.615 --> 00:41:34.080 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: That's right.

00:41:34.080 --> 00:41:35.150 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: It makes total sense.

00:41:35.150 --> 00:41:35.858 align:middle line:90%
It's interesting.

00:41:35.858 --> 00:41:37.067 align:middle line:90%
I've never heard that before.

00:41:37.067 --> 00:41:38.899 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: So this
is all part of creating

00:41:38.899 --> 00:41:39.840 align:middle line:90%
the bad neighborhood.

00:41:39.840 --> 00:41:41.869 align:middle line:84%
We used to think about
things like breast cancer

00:41:41.869 --> 00:41:43.660 align:middle line:84%
as being-- this is
something that I learned

00:41:43.660 --> 00:41:46.550 align:middle line:84%
from Susan Love, who has been
one of my mentors for a while.

00:41:46.550 --> 00:41:49.060 align:middle line:84%
She's a breast cancer
advocate and surgeon.

00:41:49.060 --> 00:41:51.940 align:middle line:84%
And she said, we used
to think, 20 years ago,

00:41:51.940 --> 00:41:54.960 align:middle line:84%
that you would have
a breast cancer cell.

00:41:54.960 --> 00:41:56.197 align:middle line:90%
And it would divide.

00:41:56.197 --> 00:41:57.530 align:middle line:90%
You'd have these daughter cells.

00:41:57.530 --> 00:42:00.170 align:middle line:84%
It would turn into a
mass that you would maybe

00:42:00.170 --> 00:42:03.690 align:middle line:84%
see on a mammogram, or you
would detect clinically,

00:42:03.690 --> 00:42:05.180 align:middle line:90%
or feel it yourself.

00:42:05.180 --> 00:42:07.270 align:middle line:90%
And we don't think that anymore.

00:42:07.270 --> 00:42:10.010 align:middle line:84%
What we think now is that
we all have mutated cells

00:42:10.010 --> 00:42:11.230 align:middle line:90%
all the time.

00:42:11.230 --> 00:42:13.172 align:middle line:84%
And it's a matter of
what kind of neighborhood

00:42:13.172 --> 00:42:14.505 align:middle line:90%
you're creating for those cells.

00:42:14.505 --> 00:42:15.630 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: The environment.

00:42:15.630 --> 00:42:16.360 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: The environment.

00:42:16.360 --> 00:42:18.290 align:middle line:84%
So when you are creating
a good neighborhood,

00:42:18.290 --> 00:42:20.280 align:middle line:90%
you have the girl scouts.

00:42:20.280 --> 00:42:23.450 align:middle line:84%
You have healthy, beautiful
vegetables every day,

00:42:23.450 --> 00:42:25.110 align:middle line:90%
five to seven colors.

00:42:25.110 --> 00:42:27.790 align:middle line:84%
You're moderating how
much alcohol you have.

00:42:27.790 --> 00:42:29.910 align:middle line:84%
You're eating the dark
chocolate, but not

00:42:29.910 --> 00:42:31.210 align:middle line:90%
two bars or one bar.

00:42:31.210 --> 00:42:33.170 align:middle line:84%
You're having a
couple of squares.

00:42:33.170 --> 00:42:36.480 align:middle line:84%
When you do that, you're
creating a good neighborhood.

00:42:36.480 --> 00:42:39.420 align:middle line:84%
When you're someone who's
hearing jungle drums unless you

00:42:39.420 --> 00:42:43.230 align:middle line:84%
have a doughnut, and cortisol
is running like crazy,

00:42:43.230 --> 00:42:46.140 align:middle line:84%
and you're drinking
more than the right dose

00:42:46.140 --> 00:42:49.500 align:middle line:84%
of coffee in the morning, you
are down that slippery slope

00:42:49.500 --> 00:42:50.910 align:middle line:90%
of creating a bad neighborhood.

00:42:50.910 --> 00:42:53.380 align:middle line:84%
And that is not a
good epigenetic thing.

00:42:53.380 --> 00:42:54.051 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:42:54.051 --> 00:42:54.550 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:42:54.550 --> 00:42:56.460 align:middle line:90%
Interesting.

00:42:56.460 --> 00:42:57.470 align:middle line:90%
And thank you for that.

00:42:57.470 --> 00:43:00.280 align:middle line:84%
I mean, the just
distinguishing also

00:43:00.280 --> 00:43:02.701 align:middle line:84%
between the chocolate
cake versus the 80 to 90%

00:43:02.701 --> 00:43:05.200 align:middle line:84%
couple of squares of chocolate
and what it does to cortisol.

00:43:05.200 --> 00:43:06.940 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: Well, we
need substitutes, right?

00:43:06.940 --> 00:43:07.160 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: We need substitute.

00:43:07.160 --> 00:43:08.880 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: I'm not a big
fan of depriving women.

00:43:08.880 --> 00:43:09.475 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: No no, I'm not either.

00:43:09.475 --> 00:43:11.720 align:middle line:84%
And I think that's an
excellent substitute.

00:43:11.720 --> 00:43:14.310 align:middle line:84%
I want to get into some
other areas as well.

00:43:14.310 --> 00:43:17.150 align:middle line:84%
And that is, you said early
on-- let's talk a little bit,

00:43:17.150 --> 00:43:21.900 align:middle line:84%
because I want to take the time
to go through some of the more

00:43:21.900 --> 00:43:24.825 align:middle line:84%
natural ways to approach
birth control, for example.

00:43:24.825 --> 00:43:25.635 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: Yes.

00:43:25.635 --> 00:43:28.350 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: You're not a fan of
birth control pills anymore.

00:43:28.350 --> 00:43:33.254 align:middle line:10%
What long term,
by way of studies,

00:43:33.254 --> 00:43:35.170 align:middle line:10%
have they found out about
birth control pills?

00:43:35.170 --> 00:43:36.961 align:middle line:10%
And what are you noticing
in the women that

00:43:36.961 --> 00:43:38.629 align:middle line:10%
have been on them for
quite a long time?

00:43:38.629 --> 00:43:40.170 align:middle line:10%
>>GOTTFRIED: Well,
there's some brand

00:43:40.170 --> 00:43:42.128 align:middle line:10%
new data about birth
control pills that I think

00:43:42.128 --> 00:43:45.180 align:middle line:10%
are so important to talk about
because no one is talking

00:43:45.180 --> 00:43:46.720 align:middle line:10%
about this.

00:43:46.720 --> 00:43:50.520 align:middle line:10%
We've known for a long time that
when you go on a birth control

00:43:50.520 --> 00:43:55.010 align:middle line:10%
pill, it actually robs
you of testosterone.

00:43:55.010 --> 00:43:58.170 align:middle line:84%
So the birth control pill
is another synthetic form

00:43:58.170 --> 00:43:59.540 align:middle line:90%
of estrogen and progesterone.

00:43:59.540 --> 00:44:01.937 align:middle line:84%
When you go on it, it
raises another hormone.

00:44:01.937 --> 00:44:04.020 align:middle line:84%
You mentioned that your
audience is sophisticated,

00:44:04.020 --> 00:44:05.436 align:middle line:84%
so I'll just mention
this hormone.

00:44:05.436 --> 00:44:07.940 align:middle line:84%
It's called sex hormone
binding globulin.

00:44:07.940 --> 00:44:10.900 align:middle line:84%
It's kind of like a sponge
that basically soaks up

00:44:10.900 --> 00:44:13.830 align:middle line:84%
the free testosterone
in your body.

00:44:13.830 --> 00:44:18.850 align:middle line:84%
And the great irony here is that
for women who are having sex,

00:44:18.850 --> 00:44:22.400 align:middle line:84%
maybe for the first time,
maybe they're 22 years old

00:44:22.400 --> 00:44:24.970 align:middle line:84%
and having sex for
the first time,

00:44:24.970 --> 00:44:27.200 align:middle line:90%
they've got this normal libido.

00:44:27.200 --> 00:44:28.910 align:middle line:84%
They go on the
birth control pill.

00:44:28.910 --> 00:44:32.590 align:middle line:84%
Their testosterone goes from
normal down to almost nothing.

00:44:32.590 --> 00:44:35.290 align:middle line:90%
And they don't want to have sex.

00:44:35.290 --> 00:44:38.470 align:middle line:84%
Not only that, but
it actually affects

00:44:38.470 --> 00:44:40.940 align:middle line:90%
the receptors in their vagina.

00:44:40.940 --> 00:44:44.550 align:middle line:90%
And 20% have vaginal dryness.

00:44:44.550 --> 00:44:45.955 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: At 20, 25 years old.

00:44:45.955 --> 00:44:46.360 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: And
they're thinking,

00:44:46.360 --> 00:44:49.260 align:middle line:84%
why am I having these symptoms
that my mother is having,

00:44:49.260 --> 00:44:50.620 align:middle line:90%
who's going through menopause?

00:44:50.620 --> 00:44:52.328 align:middle line:10%
Or they feel like
they're doing something

00:44:52.328 --> 00:44:54.080 align:middle line:10%
wrong because nobody
talks about this.

00:44:54.080 --> 00:44:59.510 align:middle line:10%
They also have up to 20%
shrinkage of their clitoris

00:44:59.510 --> 00:45:01.380 align:middle line:10%
as a result of this
change in your hormones.

00:45:01.380 --> 00:45:04.590 align:middle line:10%
So no, I'm not a big fan
of the birth control pill.

00:45:04.590 --> 00:45:07.170 align:middle line:10%
I don't want to mess
with what I think

00:45:07.170 --> 00:45:09.216 align:middle line:10%
is the innate
intelligence of the body.

00:45:09.216 --> 00:45:10.590 align:middle line:84%
We've got to figure
out how do we

00:45:10.590 --> 00:45:12.740 align:middle line:84%
work with the innate
intelligence of the body,

00:45:12.740 --> 00:45:13.470 align:middle line:90%
not against it.

00:45:13.470 --> 00:45:15.880 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So in this day,
what do you recommend?

00:45:15.880 --> 00:45:18.850 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: I'm a big
fan of barrier methods.

00:45:18.850 --> 00:45:21.140 align:middle line:84%
The problem here is that we
don't have enough options.

00:45:21.140 --> 00:45:22.134 align:middle line:90%
We need more options.

00:45:22.134 --> 00:45:23.050 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: So condoms--

00:45:23.050 --> 00:45:24.633 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: Vasectomy
is my favorite.

00:45:24.633 --> 00:45:26.540 align:middle line:84%
But if we're talking
about a 20-something,

00:45:26.540 --> 00:45:31.980 align:middle line:84%
I would say consider
the copper IUD.

00:45:31.980 --> 00:45:33.430 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:45:33.430 --> 00:45:34.180 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: Yeah.

00:45:34.180 --> 00:45:35.380 align:middle line:90%
So very effective.

00:45:35.380 --> 00:45:37.630 align:middle line:84%
It's actually as effective
as getting your tubes tied,

00:45:37.630 --> 00:45:38.150 align:middle line:90%
but it's reversible.

00:45:38.150 --> 00:45:39.160 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But you
used to hear everyone,

00:45:39.160 --> 00:45:40.757 align:middle line:84%
and these horrible
things happened.

00:45:40.757 --> 00:45:42.340 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: So
that's from the 1970s.

00:45:42.340 --> 00:45:43.670 align:middle line:90%
We've got to rebrand IUDs.

00:45:43.670 --> 00:45:43.960 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:45:43.960 --> 00:45:45.168 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: Here's the deal.

00:45:45.168 --> 00:45:46.990 align:middle line:84%
Can I give you one
little thing on IUDs?

00:45:46.990 --> 00:45:48.280 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah, please.

00:45:48.280 --> 00:45:50.780 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: I have a few things
that I'm a crusader around.

00:45:50.780 --> 00:45:53.110 align:middle line:84%
One's vaginal dryness,
the other's IUDs.

00:45:53.110 --> 00:46:00.600 align:middle line:84%
So we know that
women who use IUDs

00:46:00.600 --> 00:46:03.860 align:middle line:84%
are the happiest
customers of all

00:46:03.860 --> 00:46:05.360 align:middle line:90%
when it comes to contraceptives.

00:46:05.360 --> 00:46:07.210 align:middle line:84%
They have the highest
satisfaction rates.

00:46:07.210 --> 00:46:10.800 align:middle line:84%
I've had three and I know
what they mean by this.

00:46:10.800 --> 00:46:14.070 align:middle line:84%
It also has the
lowest rate of usage.

00:46:14.070 --> 00:46:15.890 align:middle line:90%
So there's a total disconnect.

00:46:15.890 --> 00:46:18.190 align:middle line:84%
Highest satisfaction,
lowest usage.

00:46:18.190 --> 00:46:21.090 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And what about
any kind of problems?

00:46:21.090 --> 00:46:23.730 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: Well, we know
that one out of three women,

00:46:23.730 --> 00:46:26.730 align:middle line:84%
when they get a copper IUD, will
have some increased bleeding.

00:46:26.730 --> 00:46:29.790 align:middle line:84%
I had that when I had
my copper IUD put in,

00:46:29.790 --> 00:46:31.290 align:middle line:90%
but it's manageable.

00:46:31.290 --> 00:46:33.490 align:middle line:84%
It usually resolves
within a couple of months.

00:46:33.490 --> 00:46:35.910 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: And doesn't cause
any long-term kind of effects.

00:46:35.910 --> 00:46:37.020 align:middle line:10%
>>GOTTFRIED: Doesn't
cause long-term problems.

00:46:37.020 --> 00:46:39.280 align:middle line:10%
The problem was
actually in the 1970s,

00:46:39.280 --> 00:46:41.350 align:middle line:10%
when the Dalkon shield came out.

00:46:41.350 --> 00:46:44.260 align:middle line:10%
And it was like a
neon sign for bacteria

00:46:44.260 --> 00:46:46.490 align:middle line:10%
to come up inside the uterus.

00:46:46.490 --> 00:46:49.040 align:middle line:10%
That particular IUD
was terrible and it

00:46:49.040 --> 00:46:50.220 align:middle line:10%
got taken off the market.

00:46:50.220 --> 00:46:52.620 align:middle line:84%
But the problem is
the negative attitude

00:46:52.620 --> 00:46:54.280 align:middle line:84%
toward IUDs got
applied everywhere.

00:46:54.280 --> 00:46:55.750 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Absolutely, yeah.

00:46:55.750 --> 00:46:58.299 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: So we've got
to rebrand IUDs together.

00:46:58.299 --> 00:46:58.840 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:46:58.840 --> 00:46:59.805 align:middle line:90%
So, there we go.

00:46:59.805 --> 00:47:01.982 align:middle line:84%
So that would be your
number one choice.

00:47:01.982 --> 00:47:02.690 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: Yes.

00:47:02.690 --> 00:47:03.620 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So we'll let
people run with that.

00:47:03.620 --> 00:47:05.660 align:middle line:90%
And barriers, condoms, and--

00:47:05.660 --> 00:47:05.940 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED:
Condoms, diaphragms.

00:47:05.940 --> 00:47:06.530 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah, diaphragms.

00:47:06.530 --> 00:47:08.363 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: I'm a big
fan of the diaphragm.

00:47:08.363 --> 00:47:09.110 align:middle line:90%
You combine that.

00:47:09.110 --> 00:47:12.790 align:middle line:84%
If you are, like, a fertile
myrtle, and your partner

00:47:12.790 --> 00:47:14.370 align:middle line:84%
looks at you and
you get pregnant,

00:47:14.370 --> 00:47:15.954 align:middle line:84%
then what you want
to do is combine

00:47:15.954 --> 00:47:17.870 align:middle line:84%
some of these methods
that are less effective,

00:47:17.870 --> 00:47:20.970 align:middle line:84%
like the diaphragm, maybe
together with a condom,

00:47:20.970 --> 00:47:23.550 align:middle line:84%
especially around the time
that you're ovulating.

00:47:23.550 --> 00:47:26.200 align:middle line:84%
Or use a little bit of
natural family planning.

00:47:26.200 --> 00:47:29.630 align:middle line:84%
Have orgasmic meditation
instead of intercourse

00:47:29.630 --> 00:47:30.970 align:middle line:90%
when you're ovulation.

00:47:30.970 --> 00:47:34.009 align:middle line:84%
So I would say get creative
about how to work with this.

00:47:34.009 --> 00:47:34.550 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:47:34.550 --> 00:47:38.920 align:middle line:84%
Now let's talk about
women who have started

00:47:38.920 --> 00:47:40.420 align:middle line:84%
going into this
imbalance hormonally

00:47:40.420 --> 00:47:44.880 align:middle line:84%
and are now looking for--
Premarin's not the option.

00:47:44.880 --> 00:47:46.980 align:middle line:84%
They're now looking for
bioidentical hormones.

00:47:46.980 --> 00:47:48.717 align:middle line:84%
And at the same
time, they've heard

00:47:48.717 --> 00:47:52.429 align:middle line:84%
of Suzanne Somer's information
the last decade, a decade ago.

00:47:52.429 --> 00:47:54.220 align:middle line:84%
And then they started
hearing oh my god, it

00:47:54.220 --> 00:47:56.950 align:middle line:84%
increases rates of breast
cancer, for example.

00:47:56.950 --> 00:48:00.690 align:middle line:84%
What is the truth about
bioidentical hormones?

00:48:00.690 --> 00:48:02.660 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: So the
truth about bioidenticals

00:48:02.660 --> 00:48:07.340 align:middle line:84%
is actually that there's a
time and a place for them.

00:48:07.340 --> 00:48:09.830 align:middle line:84%
For women who are exquisitely
sensitive to estrogen-- when

00:48:09.830 --> 00:48:11.790 align:middle line:84%
I have women who come to
see me in my practice,

00:48:11.790 --> 00:48:16.050 align:middle line:84%
like I have a woman named
Sarah who came to see me.

00:48:16.050 --> 00:48:17.880 align:middle line:90%
And she just felt flat.

00:48:17.880 --> 00:48:26.570 align:middle line:84%
54 years old, really felt like
she lost her sense of herself.

00:48:26.570 --> 00:48:27.410 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Her mojo.

00:48:27.410 --> 00:48:29.970 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: Her mojo, her juju.

00:48:29.970 --> 00:48:33.140 align:middle line:84%
She wasn't feeling juicy and
on it like she used to be.

00:48:33.140 --> 00:48:36.080 align:middle line:84%
She didn't feel as at
home in her body the way

00:48:36.080 --> 00:48:37.680 align:middle line:90%
that she used to.

00:48:37.680 --> 00:48:41.680 align:middle line:84%
And she also felt more
flat in terms of her mood.

00:48:41.680 --> 00:48:44.359 align:middle line:84%
So for her, what we
decided-- we went

00:48:44.359 --> 00:48:46.400 align:middle line:84%
through what I call the
Gottfried Protocol, where

00:48:46.400 --> 00:48:49.040 align:middle line:84%
we start off with how you eat,
move, think, and supplement.

00:48:49.040 --> 00:48:51.300 align:middle line:84%
Let's get cortisol
on your side again.

00:48:51.300 --> 00:48:54.060 align:middle line:84%
Not depleting you of these
really happy hormones,

00:48:54.060 --> 00:48:57.010 align:middle line:84%
like testosterone, and
estrogen, and so forth.

00:48:57.010 --> 00:48:59.780 align:middle line:84%
And then we also tried
some botanical therapies.

00:48:59.780 --> 00:49:03.190 align:middle line:84%
But when it comes to this
particular issue in menopause,

00:49:03.190 --> 00:49:06.550 align:middle line:84%
the botanicals are
not so effective.

00:49:06.550 --> 00:49:10.590 align:middle line:84%
So with her mood
issues in particular--

00:49:10.590 --> 00:49:12.790 align:middle line:84%
there's a subset
of women, 20 to 30%

00:49:12.790 --> 00:49:14.915 align:middle line:84%
that I found in my practice
over the past 20 years,

00:49:14.915 --> 00:49:19.890 align:middle line:84%
who are exquisitely sensitive to
estrogen as a mood stabilizer.

00:49:19.890 --> 00:49:22.350 align:middle line:84%
And when you put
them on estrogen,

00:49:22.350 --> 00:49:25.790 align:middle line:84%
they just overnight
feel giggly and back

00:49:25.790 --> 00:49:27.250 align:middle line:90%
home in their body again.

00:49:27.250 --> 00:49:30.220 align:middle line:84%
So I feel like there is a
time and a place for hormones.

00:49:30.220 --> 00:49:34.420 align:middle line:84%
But I really believe you want
to do that work upstream first.

00:49:34.420 --> 00:49:37.450 align:middle line:84%
You want to get the
food, the supplements,

00:49:37.450 --> 00:49:39.350 align:middle line:90%
fill in the nutritional gaps.

00:49:39.350 --> 00:49:41.435 align:middle line:84%
Do that work first
because then your dose

00:49:41.435 --> 00:49:42.560 align:middle line:90%
is going to be a lot lower.

00:49:42.560 --> 00:49:44.580 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: The meditative
practices, all of that.

00:49:44.580 --> 00:49:44.850 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: Absolutely.

00:49:44.850 --> 00:49:46.940 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So do the
lifestyle and food changes

00:49:46.940 --> 00:49:49.180 align:middle line:84%
in advance as your
primary maintenance.

00:49:49.180 --> 00:49:52.660 align:middle line:84%
Then you're saying as an add-on
if you're a candidate for it,

00:49:52.660 --> 00:49:54.590 align:middle line:90%
a bioidentical can be good.

00:49:54.590 --> 00:49:58.280 align:middle line:84%
What about the subject of
increased cancer rates?

00:49:58.280 --> 00:50:00.550 align:middle line:90%
Breast cancer, for example.

00:50:00.550 --> 00:50:02.980 align:middle line:84%
What was that in
relationship to?

00:50:02.980 --> 00:50:04.620 align:middle line:90%
Was that bioidenticals?

00:50:04.620 --> 00:50:06.090 align:middle line:90%
Was that pharmaceuticals?

00:50:06.090 --> 00:50:06.745 align:middle line:90%
What was it?

00:50:06.745 --> 00:50:07.949 align:middle line:90%
What is it?

00:50:07.949 --> 00:50:09.740 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: So this
is the situation again

00:50:09.740 --> 00:50:13.440 align:middle line:84%
where we want to know what
does the data show us.

00:50:13.440 --> 00:50:16.170 align:middle line:84%
And we don't have data to
answer all of these questions,

00:50:16.170 --> 00:50:17.340 align:middle line:90%
unfortunately.

00:50:17.340 --> 00:50:20.960 align:middle line:84%
What we know is that it's
probably not a good idea

00:50:20.960 --> 00:50:25.370 align:middle line:84%
to go on external
hormones forever.

00:50:25.370 --> 00:50:27.869 align:middle line:84%
So just with what we
know about something

00:50:27.869 --> 00:50:29.535 align:middle line:84%
called hormone
resistance-- you probably

00:50:29.535 --> 00:50:30.670 align:middle line:84%
have heard of
insulin resistance.

00:50:30.670 --> 00:50:30.960 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:50:30.960 --> 00:50:33.001 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: You can have
hormone resistance that

00:50:33.001 --> 00:50:35.670 align:middle line:84%
develops if you're just taking
the same dose of some hormone

00:50:35.670 --> 00:50:37.390 align:middle line:84%
externally once you
go through menopause.

00:50:37.390 --> 00:50:39.070 align:middle line:84%
So I'm not a big
fan of that either.

00:50:39.070 --> 00:50:40.860 align:middle line:84%
I'm a big fan of
this middle path

00:50:40.860 --> 00:50:44.310 align:middle line:84%
of really understanding,
OK, how can I

00:50:44.310 --> 00:50:49.770 align:middle line:84%
get my neurohormonal
dashboard to support me?

00:50:49.770 --> 00:50:52.910 align:middle line:84%
How could I manage it in a
way that really works for me,

00:50:52.910 --> 00:50:55.780 align:middle line:84%
and is calibrated and
individualized for me?

00:50:55.780 --> 00:50:59.240 align:middle line:84%
So taking this particular
issue of cancer.

00:50:59.240 --> 00:51:01.570 align:middle line:84%
We talked about the
bad neighborhood.

00:51:01.570 --> 00:51:06.120 align:middle line:10%
And what we know is that
the synthetic hormones

00:51:06.120 --> 00:51:09.000 align:middle line:10%
are definitely dangerous
and provocative.

00:51:09.000 --> 00:51:11.520 align:middle line:10%
And from the Women's Health
Initiative, what we really

00:51:11.520 --> 00:51:13.130 align:middle line:10%
believe when it comes
to breast cancer

00:51:13.130 --> 00:51:16.230 align:middle line:10%
is that it's the
synthetic progestin that's

00:51:16.230 --> 00:51:17.580 align:middle line:10%
the bad player.

00:51:17.580 --> 00:51:20.760 align:middle line:10%
So even the devil we
know, which is Premarin,

00:51:20.760 --> 00:51:23.640 align:middle line:10%
it does increase
your risk of stroke,

00:51:23.640 --> 00:51:26.810 align:middle line:10%
but it doesn't seem to have
these other ill effects,

00:51:26.810 --> 00:51:29.060 align:middle line:10%
like cancer effects,
that you see

00:51:29.060 --> 00:51:31.090 align:middle line:10%
from the synthetic progestin.

00:51:31.090 --> 00:51:35.500 align:middle line:10%
We do not have large-scale
randomized trials

00:51:35.500 --> 00:51:37.870 align:middle line:10%
that go on for years and
years, like the Women's Health

00:51:37.870 --> 00:51:40.420 align:middle line:10%
Initiative, for bioidenticals.

00:51:40.420 --> 00:51:44.580 align:middle line:84%
We have a lesser quality
study, observational studies,

00:51:44.580 --> 00:51:46.440 align:middle line:90%
especially from Europe.

00:51:46.440 --> 00:51:49.210 align:middle line:84%
And they suggest
that there's a lower

00:51:49.210 --> 00:51:52.470 align:middle line:84%
rate of breast cancer for
women who take bioidenticals.

00:51:52.470 --> 00:51:54.960 align:middle line:84%
But my way of looking at this
is it's a little bit more

00:51:54.960 --> 00:51:56.670 align:middle line:90%
nuanced than that.

00:51:56.670 --> 00:52:00.070 align:middle line:84%
We want to do randomized
trials because that's

00:52:00.070 --> 00:52:01.780 align:middle line:90%
the way that we minimize bias.

00:52:01.780 --> 00:52:04.230 align:middle line:84%
We minimize the effect of
the pharmaceutical industry,

00:52:04.230 --> 00:52:05.580 align:middle line:90%
for instance.

00:52:05.580 --> 00:52:08.590 align:middle line:10%
And when it comes
to bioidenticals,

00:52:08.590 --> 00:52:12.674 align:middle line:10%
the problem here is the one size
fits all way of approaching it.

00:52:12.674 --> 00:52:14.340 align:middle line:10%
So if you do a study,
and you're looking

00:52:14.340 --> 00:52:18.800 align:middle line:10%
at women who were on, say,
the same dose of estrodiol,

00:52:18.800 --> 00:52:21.620 align:middle line:10%
and the same dose of
natural progesterone,

00:52:21.620 --> 00:52:26.330 align:middle line:10%
some of those women have a short
serotonin transporter gene.

00:52:26.330 --> 00:52:28.310 align:middle line:10%
So this is a really
interesting gene

00:52:28.310 --> 00:52:33.570 align:middle line:10%
that's present in 40 to
45% of Caucasian women.

00:52:33.570 --> 00:52:35.790 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: What does that
mean, functionally speaking?

00:52:35.790 --> 00:52:38.080 align:middle line:10%
>>GOTTFRIED: Yes, let me
break it down for you.

00:52:38.080 --> 00:52:41.510 align:middle line:10%
So this is a really
interesting gene

00:52:41.510 --> 00:52:44.120 align:middle line:10%
that has a few jobs in the body.

00:52:44.120 --> 00:52:49.630 align:middle line:84%
And it's in charge of how
serotonin get shuttled around

00:52:49.630 --> 00:52:54.370 align:middle line:84%
in between your brain
cells, your nerve cells.

00:52:54.370 --> 00:52:59.450 align:middle line:84%
It regulates how much your
genes in your brain cells

00:52:59.450 --> 00:53:00.510 align:middle line:90%
make serotonin.

00:53:00.510 --> 00:53:03.780 align:middle line:84%
So it's not as simple
as a quantity issue.

00:53:03.780 --> 00:53:06.000 align:middle line:10%
But you move it
around a little less

00:53:06.000 --> 00:53:09.130 align:middle line:10%
effectively if you have a
short serotonin gene, which

00:53:09.130 --> 00:53:13.747 align:middle line:10%
is the mutation, versus
a long serotonin gene.

00:53:13.747 --> 00:53:15.080 align:middle line:90%
So just to back up for a minute.

00:53:15.080 --> 00:53:17.620 align:middle line:90%


00:53:17.620 --> 00:53:20.270 align:middle line:84%
When you inherit genes
from your parents,

00:53:20.270 --> 00:53:22.360 align:middle line:90%
you get one copy from each.

00:53:22.360 --> 00:53:24.760 align:middle line:90%
And two is a complete set.

00:53:24.760 --> 00:53:28.730 align:middle line:84%
The normal serotonin transporter
gene is to be long long.

00:53:28.730 --> 00:53:31.770 align:middle line:84%
You have a long
copy of both genes.

00:53:31.770 --> 00:53:33.780 align:middle line:84%
You can have one copy
of the short gene

00:53:33.780 --> 00:53:36.200 align:middle line:84%
or you can have two
copies of the short gene,

00:53:36.200 --> 00:53:38.870 align:middle line:84%
as if you got it
from both parents.

00:53:38.870 --> 00:53:40.530 align:middle line:10%
The other thing
that this gene does,

00:53:40.530 --> 00:53:43.185 align:middle line:10%
besides give you problems
with communicating serotonin

00:53:43.185 --> 00:53:48.740 align:middle line:10%
in the brain, is that it makes
you go into hypervigilance more

00:53:48.740 --> 00:53:52.341 align:middle line:10%
readily, especially
in perimenopause.

00:53:52.341 --> 00:53:54.840 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: That's where it shows
that symptomatically, you're

00:53:54.840 --> 00:53:55.340 align:middle line:90%
saying?

00:53:55.340 --> 00:53:57.810 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: More so for
women in perimenopause,

00:53:57.810 --> 00:54:01.440 align:middle line:84%
because when women have a
normal amount of estrogen,

00:54:01.440 --> 00:54:05.330 align:middle line:84%
say up until about
age 35, 40, 45,

00:54:05.330 --> 00:54:10.080 align:middle line:84%
they behave as if they've got
two copies of the normal gene.

00:54:10.080 --> 00:54:12.640 align:middle line:84%
Now, some of this work
was done in monkeys.

00:54:12.640 --> 00:54:14.940 align:middle line:90%
We don't know as much in humans.

00:54:14.940 --> 00:54:17.560 align:middle line:84%
Is it as simple as just giving
these women estrogen and it

00:54:17.560 --> 00:54:21.720 align:middle line:84%
makes them feel like
they're not hypervigilant?

00:54:21.720 --> 00:54:24.990 align:middle line:84%
But it makes your
amygdala in your brain,

00:54:24.990 --> 00:54:26.770 align:middle line:84%
that place in your
brain where you're just

00:54:26.770 --> 00:54:28.220 align:middle line:90%
surveying for danger everywhere.

00:54:28.220 --> 00:54:28.480 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Fight or flight.

00:54:28.480 --> 00:54:29.688 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: Fight or flight.

00:54:29.688 --> 00:54:31.510 align:middle line:90%
It makes your amygdala hot.

00:54:31.510 --> 00:54:35.860 align:middle line:84%
It makes you perceive
danger everywhere you look.

00:54:35.860 --> 00:54:39.220 align:middle line:84%
And it makes you have a
stress response all the time

00:54:39.220 --> 00:54:40.470 align:middle line:90%
that's hard to turn off.

00:54:40.470 --> 00:54:44.290 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So what percentage
of people have this short gene?

00:54:44.290 --> 00:54:46.830 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: 40 to
45% of Caucasians,

00:54:46.830 --> 00:54:49.690 align:middle line:90%
so it's very common.

00:54:49.690 --> 00:54:51.330 align:middle line:84%
And the interesting
part for this

00:54:51.330 --> 00:54:53.884 align:middle line:84%
is that there's actually
some simple solutions.

00:54:53.884 --> 00:54:55.550 align:middle line:84%
One of the things
that I love talk about

00:54:55.550 --> 00:54:58.190 align:middle line:84%
is in the Gottfried
Protocol, step one--

00:54:58.190 --> 00:55:01.650 align:middle line:84%
it's this progressive way of
dealing with hormone balance.

00:55:01.650 --> 00:55:04.520 align:middle line:84%
Step one is that you
fill in nutritional gaps.

00:55:04.520 --> 00:55:07.500 align:middle line:84%
Someone who's got a short
serotonin transporter gene

00:55:07.500 --> 00:55:11.880 align:middle line:90%
needs bioactive vitamin B6.

00:55:11.880 --> 00:55:14.930 align:middle line:84%
And I can tell you, in
the 50 patients that I've

00:55:14.930 --> 00:55:17.570 align:middle line:84%
treated in the past
year who have one or two

00:55:17.570 --> 00:55:20.190 align:middle line:84%
copies of the short
serotonin transporter gene,

00:55:20.190 --> 00:55:22.020 align:middle line:84%
overnight they feel
a difference when

00:55:22.020 --> 00:55:25.610 align:middle line:84%
they get this particular
supplement, bioactive vitamin

00:55:25.610 --> 00:55:26.234 align:middle line:90%
B6.

00:55:26.234 --> 00:55:27.150 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Interesting.

00:55:27.150 --> 00:55:27.630 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:55:27.630 --> 00:55:29.255 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: So
there's ways around it.

00:55:29.255 --> 00:55:32.050 align:middle line:84%
But I think it's so important
to understand that if you're

00:55:32.050 --> 00:55:35.350 align:middle line:84%
feeling overwhelmed, if you're
feeling like a stress case,

00:55:35.350 --> 00:55:37.850 align:middle line:84%
and like your
hypervigilant, you want

00:55:37.850 --> 00:55:39.082 align:middle line:90%
to think about the biology.

00:55:39.082 --> 00:55:40.790 align:middle line:84%
Certainly there's an
emotional piece too.

00:55:40.790 --> 00:55:41.560 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Is there
a test that can

00:55:41.560 --> 00:55:43.144 align:middle line:84%
be done to determine
if you have that?

00:55:43.144 --> 00:55:43.851 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: Yes.

00:55:43.851 --> 00:55:46.630 align:middle line:84%
So there's a couple of different
ways that you can test for it.

00:55:46.630 --> 00:55:50.030 align:middle line:84%
We're getting to this era where
there's more and more testing

00:55:50.030 --> 00:55:52.930 align:middle line:84%
of genetics, which I
think is important to be

00:55:52.930 --> 00:55:54.950 align:middle line:90%
a wise, informed citizen around.

00:55:54.950 --> 00:55:56.950 align:middle line:84%
And I can tell you, most
conventional physicians

00:55:56.950 --> 00:56:00.660 align:middle line:84%
have no idea how to make
this information actionable.

00:56:00.660 --> 00:56:02.160 align:middle line:84%
So this is one of
those places where

00:56:02.160 --> 00:56:05.320 align:middle line:84%
we need to step into our
power and understand what's

00:56:05.320 --> 00:56:08.740 align:middle line:84%
going to help us if we've
got genetic issues that

00:56:08.740 --> 00:56:09.900 align:middle line:90%
are part of our challenge.

00:56:09.900 --> 00:56:12.550 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So I want
to ask you one more

00:56:12.550 --> 00:56:14.120 align:middle line:84%
thing about
replacement, and that

00:56:14.120 --> 00:56:17.560 align:middle line:84%
is, what about
homeopathic hormones?

00:56:17.560 --> 00:56:19.150 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: So
homeopathic remedies

00:56:19.150 --> 00:56:20.620 align:middle line:90%
are really interesting.

00:56:20.620 --> 00:56:23.110 align:middle line:84%
The way that I answer a
question like that is always

00:56:23.110 --> 00:56:26.244 align:middle line:84%
to go back to my inner
geek, because you know--

00:56:26.244 --> 00:56:27.160 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: And you are.

00:56:27.160 --> 00:56:28.640 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED:
 --Harvard-MIT-physician-scientist.

00:56:28.640 --> 00:56:30.014 align:middle line:84%
So I always go to
the data first.

00:56:30.014 --> 00:56:31.810 align:middle line:90%
What does the science tell us?

00:56:31.810 --> 00:56:35.080 align:middle line:84%
And then I'll bring in maybe
some of my anecdotal experience

00:56:35.080 --> 00:56:36.720 align:middle line:84%
of working with
people for 20 years,

00:56:36.720 --> 00:56:38.130 align:middle line:90%
but I start with the hard data.

00:56:38.130 --> 00:56:39.930 align:middle line:90%
I think hard data's super sexy.

00:56:39.930 --> 00:56:49.240 align:middle line:84%
So when it comes to this
issue of what do we do--

00:56:49.240 --> 00:56:53.250 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Some people call it
almost a whisper of hormones

00:56:53.250 --> 00:56:55.330 align:middle line:84%
when they're talking about
homeopathic hormones.

00:56:55.330 --> 00:56:55.810 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: Right.

00:56:55.810 --> 00:56:57.290 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But they
can be effective.

00:56:57.290 --> 00:56:58.789 align:middle line:84%
And we only have a
few minutes left,

00:56:58.789 --> 00:57:01.812 align:middle line:84%
and I want to ask you about
the testing and such too.

00:57:01.812 --> 00:57:02.520 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: Yes.

00:57:02.520 --> 00:57:04.920 align:middle line:10%
So when it comes
to homeopathics,

00:57:04.920 --> 00:57:07.500 align:middle line:10%
they're proven to be
effective for certain things.

00:57:07.500 --> 00:57:09.230 align:middle line:10%
I'm a big fan of
homeopathic remedies,

00:57:09.230 --> 00:57:11.260 align:middle line:10%
especially for my
children, especially

00:57:11.260 --> 00:57:14.920 align:middle line:10%
for allergies and some of the
other inflammatory conditions

00:57:14.920 --> 00:57:18.010 align:middle line:10%
that we face, chronic
inflammatory conditions.

00:57:18.010 --> 00:57:20.900 align:middle line:84%
I haven't been super
impressed with some

00:57:20.900 --> 00:57:25.210 align:middle line:84%
of the homeopathic remedies
from a randomized control trial

00:57:25.210 --> 00:57:25.930 align:middle line:90%
perspective.

00:57:25.930 --> 00:57:27.890 align:middle line:84%
Now, part of the
problem is we don't

00:57:27.890 --> 00:57:30.310 align:middle line:84%
have a ton of money from
the government going

00:57:30.310 --> 00:57:33.100 align:middle line:84%
into big randomized
trials looking

00:57:33.100 --> 00:57:34.340 align:middle line:90%
at homeopathic remedies.

00:57:34.340 --> 00:57:38.100 align:middle line:84%
So it may be more a matter
that we don't have the science

00:57:38.100 --> 00:57:40.030 align:middle line:90%
to say that it's good or bad.

00:57:40.030 --> 00:57:42.550 align:middle line:84%
And so in that situation,
you have to do an experiment

00:57:42.550 --> 00:57:43.910 align:middle line:90%
and see if it works for you.

00:57:43.910 --> 00:57:44.490 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:57:44.490 --> 00:57:47.400 align:middle line:84%
We'll leave it at that because
it is a more esoteric area

00:57:47.400 --> 00:57:50.750 align:middle line:84%
anyway, not that many people
are even prescribing them.

00:57:50.750 --> 00:57:55.790 align:middle line:84%
Now let's get into the
various modalities of testing.

00:57:55.790 --> 00:58:00.180 align:middle line:84%
We only have three minutes
left, so it's just zipped by.

00:58:00.180 --> 00:58:05.732 align:middle line:84%
Mammograms or thermography,
which one would you recommend?

00:58:05.732 --> 00:58:07.440 align:middle line:84%
>>GOTTFRIED: There's
no perfect screening

00:58:07.440 --> 00:58:08.740 align:middle line:90%
test for breast cancer.

00:58:08.740 --> 00:58:11.350 align:middle line:84%
So, given our limitations--
It's kind of like contraception,

00:58:11.350 --> 00:58:12.050 align:middle line:90%
honestly.

00:58:12.050 --> 00:58:13.450 align:middle line:90%
We've got lousy options.

00:58:13.450 --> 00:58:19.300 align:middle line:84%
So to me, a digital
mammogram every two

00:58:19.300 --> 00:58:22.300 align:middle line:84%
years after the age of 50, which
is what the US Preventative

00:58:22.300 --> 00:58:24.530 align:middle line:84%
Task Force rating
recommends, that's

00:58:24.530 --> 00:58:26.280 align:middle line:84%
where I think we are
in terms of the data.

00:58:26.280 --> 00:58:28.650 align:middle line:84%
I think the data looking
at women younger than that,

00:58:28.650 --> 00:58:32.180 align:middle line:84%
it's only worthwhile
if you're high risk.

00:58:32.180 --> 00:58:33.590 align:middle line:90%
I'm a big fan of thermograms.

00:58:33.590 --> 00:58:35.630 align:middle line:84%
They detect whether you
have hormone imbalance

00:58:35.630 --> 00:58:37.580 align:middle line:84%
or inflammation,
but I don't think

00:58:37.580 --> 00:58:39.430 align:middle line:90%
they're perfect on their own.

00:58:39.430 --> 00:58:40.870 align:middle line:84%
There's no perfect
screening test.

00:58:40.870 --> 00:58:42.869 align:middle line:84%
And so one of the things
I recommend, especially

00:58:42.869 --> 00:58:45.120 align:middle line:84%
with the new guidelines that
we have with mammograms,

00:58:45.120 --> 00:58:46.900 align:middle line:84%
is that you get your
first mammogram,

00:58:46.900 --> 00:58:49.620 align:middle line:90%
if you're low risk, at age 50.

00:58:49.620 --> 00:58:51.637 align:middle line:84%
Digital, because it's
lower in radiation.

00:58:51.637 --> 00:58:53.970 align:middle line:84%
Go to a place where they
really know what they're doing,

00:58:53.970 --> 00:58:56.180 align:middle line:84%
such as UCSF, which
is a world leader.

00:58:56.180 --> 00:59:00.320 align:middle line:84%
And then to do the thermogram
every alternating year

00:59:00.320 --> 00:59:02.580 align:middle line:84%
so that you have a screening
test that you're doing.

00:59:02.580 --> 00:59:03.270 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:59:03.270 --> 00:59:03.770 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:59:03.770 --> 00:59:05.210 align:middle line:90%
Thank you on that.

00:59:05.210 --> 00:59:07.279 align:middle line:90%
That's very useful information.

00:59:07.279 --> 00:59:08.820 align:middle line:84%
Now let's look about
the other tests.

00:59:08.820 --> 00:59:11.280 align:middle line:84%
If we want to do a profile--
we have just a couple minutes

00:59:11.280 --> 00:59:14.550 align:middle line:84%
left-- do we do the saliva
tests, hair tests, blood tests?

00:59:14.550 --> 00:59:15.686 align:middle line:90%
What do we do?

00:59:15.686 --> 00:59:17.810 align:middle line:10%
>>GOTTFRIED: I typically
start with the blood tests

00:59:17.810 --> 00:59:20.390 align:middle line:10%
because it's the language
of conventional physicians.

00:59:20.390 --> 00:59:23.500 align:middle line:10%
And I really want to
bridge together this divide

00:59:23.500 --> 00:59:25.280 align:middle line:10%
that we have between
conventional medicine

00:59:25.280 --> 00:59:26.790 align:middle line:10%
and alternative medicine.

00:59:26.790 --> 00:59:29.040 align:middle line:84%
So I am a big fan
of blood testing.

00:59:29.040 --> 00:59:32.620 align:middle line:84%
The problem is it's a
snapshot of the six seconds

00:59:32.620 --> 00:59:34.199 align:middle line:90%
that a needle's in your vein.

00:59:34.199 --> 00:59:35.740 align:middle line:84%
But it's a good
place to start if you

00:59:35.740 --> 00:59:38.487 align:middle line:84%
want to look at your cortisol,
your DHEA, the balance

00:59:38.487 --> 00:59:40.070 align:middle line:84%
between your estrogen
and progesterone

00:59:40.070 --> 00:59:43.300 align:middle line:84%
and your androgens, it's
a good place to start.

00:59:43.300 --> 00:59:47.190 align:middle line:84%
If you find that you have
a problem with cortisol,

00:59:47.190 --> 00:59:49.940 align:middle line:84%
like I did when I measured
my blood in my 30s,

00:59:49.940 --> 00:59:52.860 align:middle line:84%
then you want to actually
do some more nuanced tests.

00:59:52.860 --> 00:59:56.240 align:middle line:84%
And that's where I think
saliva testing can be helpful.

00:59:56.240 --> 00:59:59.820 align:middle line:84%
So there's pluses and minuses
of each form of testing.

00:59:59.820 --> 01:00:02.450 align:middle line:84%
The other problem is this
issue of hormone resistance.

01:00:02.450 --> 01:00:04.750 align:middle line:84%
So if we go back to the woman
with the short serotonin

01:00:04.750 --> 01:00:07.930 align:middle line:84%
transporter gene,
for instance, she

01:00:07.930 --> 01:00:11.590 align:middle line:84%
develops cortisol
resistance, where

01:00:11.590 --> 01:00:14.110 align:middle line:84%
the level that you measure
of cortisol in her blood

01:00:14.110 --> 01:00:15.870 align:middle line:84%
does not necessarily
reflect what's

01:00:15.870 --> 01:00:17.580 align:middle line:90%
happening inside her cells.

01:00:17.580 --> 01:00:21.410 align:middle line:84%
And so the testing is
less helpful than asking

01:00:21.410 --> 01:00:22.967 align:middle line:84%
her questions about
her experience.

01:00:22.967 --> 01:00:25.550 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So actually spending
time with your patients, again.

01:00:25.550 --> 01:00:26.460 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: Yes, exactly.

01:00:26.460 --> 01:00:27.280 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Gee, what
a novel theory.

01:00:27.280 --> 01:00:28.020 align:middle line:90%
>>GOTTFRIED: Oh my gosh.

01:00:28.020 --> 01:00:28.770 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: And you do that.

01:00:28.770 --> 01:00:29.850 align:middle line:90%
You do that in spades.

